909	  - name: Create a task with the definition from the standard input and with a timer trigger that runs the task at the top of every hour using the default trigger name. Either 'Ctrl + Z'(Windows) or 'Ctrl + D'(Linux) terminates the input stream.
910	    text: |
911	        cat task.yaml | az acr task create -n hello-world -r myregistry -f - -c /dev/null \\
912	            --schedule "0 */1 * * *"
913	        az acr task create -n hello-world -r myregistry -f - -c /dev/null --schedule "0 */1 * * *"
914	  - name: Create a Linux task from a public GitHub repository which builds the hello-world image without triggers and uses a build argument.
915	    text: |
916	        az acr task create -t hello-world:{{.Run.ID}} -n hello-world -r myregistry \\
917	            -c https://github.com/Azure/acr-builder.git -f Dockerfile \\
918	            --commit-trigger-enabled false --base-image-trigger-enabled false \\
919	            --arg DOCKER_CLI_BASE_IMAGE=docker:18.03.0-ce-git
920	  - name: Create a Linux task using a specific branch of a private Azure DevOps repository which builds the hello-world image on Arm architecture (V7 variant) and has triggers enabled.
921	    text: |
922	        az acr task create -t hello-world:{{.Run.ID}} -n hello-world -r myregistry \\
923	            -c https://msazure.visualstudio.com/DefaultCollection/Project/_git/Repo#Branch:Folder \\
924	            -f Dockerfile --git-access-token <Personal Access Token> --platform linux/arm/v7
925	  - name: Create a Linux task from a public GitHub repository which builds the hello-world image with both a git commit and pull request trigger enabled. Note that this task does not use Source Registry (myregistry), so we can explicitly set Auth mode as None for it.
926	    text: |
927	        az acr task create -t hello-world:{{.Run.ID}} -n hello-world -r myregistry  -f Dockerfile \\
928	            --no-push true --auth-mode None -c https://github.com/Azure-Samples/acr-build-helloworld-node.git \\
929	            --pull-request-trigger-enabled true --git-access-token 000000000000000000000000000000000
930	  - name: Create a Windows task from a public GitHub repository which builds the Azure Container Builder image on Amd64 architecture with only base image trigger enabled.
931	    text: |
932	        az acr task create -t acb:{{.Run.ID}} -n acb-win -r myregistry \\
933	            -c https://github.com/Azure/acr-builder.git -f Windows.Dockerfile \\
934	            --commit-trigger-enabled false --platform Windows/amd64
935	  - name: Create a Linux multi-step task from a public GitHub repository with with both system-assigned and user-assigned managed identities and base image, git commit, pull request, and timer triggers that run the task at noon on Mondays through Fridays with the timer trigger name provided.
936	    text: |
937	        az acr task create -t hello-world:{{.Run.ID}} -n hello-world -r myregistry \\
938	            --pull-request-trigger-enabled true --schedule "dailyTimer:0 12 * * Mon-Fri" \\
939	            -c https://github.com/Azure-Samples/acr-tasks.git#:multipleRegistries -f testtask.yaml \\
940	            --assign-identity [system] "/subscriptions/<subscriptionId>/resourcegroups/<myResourceGroup>/providers/Microsoft.ManagedIdentity/userAssignedIdentities/<myUserAssignedIdentitiy>"
941	"""

72	  - name: --node-count -c
73	    type: int
74	    short-summary: Number of nodes in the Kubernetes node pool. After creating a cluster, you can change the size of its node pool with `az aks scale`.

The nodeIP means the VMs will be attached to the LoadBalancer by adding its private IP address to the backend pool. The nodeIPConfiguration means the VMs will be attached to the LoadBalancer by referencing the backend pool ID in the VM's NIC.

182	  - name: --outbound-type

185	    long-summary: Select between loadBalancer, userDefinedRouting, managedNATGateway, userAssignedNATGateway and none. If not set, defaults to type loadBalancer. Requires --vnet-subnet-id to be provided with a preconfigured route table and --load-balancer-sku to be Standard.

192	  - name: --enable-cluster-autoscaler
193	    type: bool

195	    long-summary: If specified, please make sure the kubernetes version is larger than 1.10.6.
196	  - name: --min-count

198	    short-summary: Minimum nodes count used for autoscaler, when "--enable-cluster-autoscaler" specified. Please specify the value in the range of [1, 1000].
199	  - name: --max-count
200	    type: int
201	    short-summary: Maximum nodes count used for autoscaler, when "--enable-cluster-autoscaler" specified. Please specify the value in the range of [1, 1000].
202	  - name: --vm-set-type
203	    type: string

205	  - name: --enable-addons -a
206	    type: string
207	    short-summary: Enable the Kubernetes addons in a comma-separated list.
208	    long-summary: |-
209	        These addons are available:
210	            - http_application_routing : configure ingress with automatic public DNS name creation.
211	            - monitoring               : turn on Log Analytics monitoring. Uses the Log Analytics Default Workspace if it exists, else creates one.
212	                                         Specify "--workspace-resource-id" to use an existing workspace.
213	                                         Specify "--enable-msi-auth-for-monitoring" to use Managed Identity Auth.
214	                                         Specify "--enable-syslog" to enable syslog data collection from nodes. Note MSI must be enabled
215	                                         Specify "--data-collection-settings" to configure data collection settings
216	                                         Specify "--ampls-resource-id" for private link. Note MSI must be enabled.
217	                                         Specify "--enable-high-log-scale-mode" to enable high log scale mode for container logs. Note MSI must be enabled.
218	                                         If monitoring addon is enabled --no-wait argument will have no effect
219	            - azure-policy             : enable Azure policy. The Azure Policy add-on for AKS enables at-scale enforcements and safeguards on your clusters in a centralized, consistent manner.
220	                                         Learn more at aka.ms/aks/policy.
221	            - virtual-node             : enable AKS Virtual Node.
222	                                         Requires --aci-subnet-name to provide the name of an existing subnet for the Virtual Node to use.
223	                                         aci-subnet-name must be in the same vnet which is specified by --vnet-subnet-id (required as well).
224	            - confcom                  : enable confcom addon, this will enable SGX device plugin by default.
225	            - open-service-mesh        : enable Open Service Mesh addon.
226	            - azure-keyvault-secrets-provider : enable Azure Keyvault Secrets Provider addon.
227	  - name: --disable-rbac
228	    type: bool
229	    short-summary: Disable Kubernetes Role-Based Access Control.
230	  - name: --max-pods -m
231	    type: int
232	    short-summary: The maximum number of pods deployable to a node.
233	    long-summary: If not specified, defaults based on network-plugin. 30 for "azure", 110 for "kubenet", or 250 for "none".
234	  - name: --network-plugin
235	    type: string
236	    short-summary: The Kubernetes network plugin to use.
237	    long-summary: Specify "azure" for routable pod IPs from VNET, "kubenet" for non-routable pod IPs with an overlay network, or "none" for no networking configured. Defaults to "kubenet".
238	  - name: --network-plugin-mode
239	    type: string
240	    short-summary: The network plugin mode to use.
241	    long-summary: |
242	        Used to control the mode the network plugin should operate in. For example, "overlay" used with
243	        --network-plugin=azure will use an overlay network (non-VNET IPs) for pods in the cluster.
244	  - name: --network-policy
245	    type: string
246	    short-summary: Network Policy Engine to use.
247	    long-summary: |
248	        Azure provides three Network Policy Engines for enforcing network policies that can be used together with "azure" network plugin. The following values can be specified:
249	          - "azure" for Azure Network Policy Manager,
250	          - "cilium" for Azure CNI Powered by Cilium,
251	          - "calico" for open-source network and network security solution founded by Tigera,
252	          - "none" when no Network Policy Engine is installed (default value).
253	        Defaults to "none" (network policy disabled).
254	  - name: --network-dataplane
255	    type: string
256	    short-summary: The network dataplane to use.
257	    long-summary: |
258	        Network dataplane used in the Kubernetes cluster.
259	        Specify "azure" to use the Azure dataplane (default) or "cilium" to enable Cilium dataplane.
260	  - name: --no-ssh-key -x
261	    type: string
262	    short-summary: Do not use or create a local SSH key.
263	    long-summary: To access nodes after creating a cluster with this option, use the Azure Portal.
264	  - name: --pod-cidr
265	    type: string
266	    short-summary: A CIDR notation IP range from which to assign pod IPs when kubenet is used.
267	    long-summary: This range must not overlap with any Subnet IP ranges. For example, 172.244.0.0/16.
268	  - name: --message-of-the-day
269	    type: string
270	    short-summary: Path to a file containing the desired message of the day. Only valid for linux nodes. Will be written to /etc/motd.
271	  - name: --service-cidr
272	    type: string
273	    short-summary: A CIDR notation IP range from which to assign service cluster IPs.
274	    long-summary: This range must not overlap with any Subnet IP ranges. For example, 10.0.0.0/16.
275	  - name: --service-cidrs
276	    type: string
277	    short-summary: A comma-separated list of CIDR notation IP ranges from which to assign service cluster IPs.
278	    long-summary: Each range must not overlap with any Subnet IP ranges. For example, "10.0.0.0/16,2001:abcd::/108".
279	  - name: --pod-cidrs
280	    type: string
281	    short-summary: A comma-separated list of CIDR notation IP ranges from which to assign pod IPs when kubenet is used.
282	    long-summary: Each range must not overlap with any Subnet IP ranges. For example, "172.244.0.0/16,fd0:abcd::/64".
283	  - name: --ip-families
284	    type: string
285	    short-summary: A comma-separated list of IP versions to use for cluster networking.
286	    long-summary: Each IP version should be in the format IPvN. For example, IPv4.
287	  - name: --vnet-subnet-id
288	    type: string
289	    short-summary: The ID of a subnet in an existing VNet into which to deploy the cluster.
290	  - name: --pod-subnet-id
291	    type: string
292	    short-summary: The ID of a subnet in an existing VNet into which to assign pods in the cluster (requires azure network-plugin).
293	  - name: --ppg
294	    type: string
295	    short-summary: The ID of a PPG.
296	  - name: --enable-node-public-ip
297	    type: bool
298	    short-summary: Enable VMSS node public IP.
299	  - name: --node-public-ip-prefix-id
300	    type: string
301	    short-summary: Public IP prefix ID used to assign public IPs to VMSS nodes.
302	  - name: --workspace-resource-id
303	    type: string
304	    short-summary: The resource ID of an existing Log Analytics Workspace to use for storing monitoring data. If not specified, uses the default Log Analytics Workspace if it exists, otherwise creates one.
305	  - name: --enable-msi-auth-for-monitoring
306	    type: bool
307	    short-summary: Enable Managed Identity Auth for Monitoring addon.
308	  - name: --enable-syslog
309	    type: bool
310	    short-summary: Enable syslog data collection for Monitoring addon
311	  - name: --data-collection-settings
312	    type: string
313	    short-summary: Path to JSON file containing data collection settings for Monitoring addon.
314	  - name: --ampls-resource-id
315	    type: string
316	    short-summary: Resource ID of Azure Monitor Private Link scope for Monitoring Addon.
317	  - name: --enable-high-log-scale-mode
318	    type: bool
319	    short-summary: Enable High Log Scale Mode for Container Logs.
320	  - name: --tier
321	    type: string
322	    short-summary: Specify SKU tier for managed clusters. '--tier standard' enables a standard managed cluster service with a financially backed SLA. '--tier free' does not have a financially backed SLA.
323	  - name: --attach-acr
324	    type: string
325	    short-summary: Grant the 'acrpull' role assignment to the ACR specified by name or resource ID.
326	  - name: --enable-private-cluster
327	    type: string
328	    short-summary: Enable private cluster.
329	  - name: --private-dns-zone
330	    type: string
331	    short-summary: Private dns zone mode for private cluster.
332	    long-summary: Allowed values are "system", "none" or custom private dns zone resource id. If not set, defaults to type system. Requires --enable-private-cluster to be used.
333	  - name: --fqdn-subdomain
334	    type: string
335	    short-summary: Prefix for FQDN that is created for private cluster with custom private dns zone scenario.
336	  - name: --disable-public-fqdn
337	    type: bool
338	    short-summary: Disable public fqdn feature for private cluster.
339	  - name: --api-server-authorized-ip-ranges
340	    type: string
341	    short-summary: Comma-separated list of authorized apiserver IP ranges. Set to 0.0.0.0/32 to restrict apiserver traffic to node pools.
342	  - name: --enable-managed-identity
343	    type: bool
344	    short-summary: Using a system assigned managed identity to manage cluster resource group. You can explicitly specify "--service-principal" and "--client-secret" to disable managed identity, otherwise it will be enabled.
345	  - name: --assign-identity
346	    type: string
347	    short-summary: Specify an existing user assigned identity for control plane's usage in order to manage cluster resource group.
348	  - name: --assign-kubelet-identity
349	    type: string
350	    short-summary: Specify an existing user assigned identity for kubelet's usage, which is typically used to pull image from ACR.
351	  - name: --node-osdisk-diskencryptionset-id -d
352	    type: string
353	    short-summary: ResourceId of the disk encryption set to use for enabling encryption at rest on agent node os disk.
354	  - name: --enable-workload-identity
355	    type: bool
356	    short-summary: Enable workload identity addon.
357	  - name: --aci-subnet-name
358	    type: string
359	    short-summary: The name of a subnet in an existing VNet into which to deploy the virtual nodes.
360	  - name: --appgw-name
361	    type: string
362	    short-summary: Name of the application gateway to create/use in the node resource group. Use with ingress-azure addon.
363	  - name: --appgw-subnet-cidr

366	  - name: --appgw-id

372	  - name: --appgw-watch-namespace
373	    type: string

375	  - name: --enable-sgxquotehelper

416	        You must set or not set --gmsa-dns-server and --gmsa-root-domain-name at the same time when setting --enable-windows-gmsa.

477	    short-summary: Enable AzureBlob CSI Driver.
478	  - name: --http-proxy-config
479	    type: string
480	    short-summary: HTTP Proxy configuration for this cluster.
481	  - name: --gpu-instance-profile
482	    type: string
483	    short-summary: GPU instance profile to partition multi-gpu Nvidia GPUs.
484	  - name: --enable-oidc-issuer
485	    type: bool
486	    short-summary: Enable OIDC issuer.
487	  - name: --enable-keda
488	    type: bool
489	    short-summary: Enable KEDA workload auto-scaler.
490	  - name: --enable-azure-monitor-metrics
491	    type: bool
492	    short-summary: Enable a kubernetes cluster with the Azure Monitor managed service for Prometheus integration.
493	  - name: --azure-monitor-workspace-resource-id
494	    type: string
495	    short-summary: Resource ID of the Azure Monitor Workspace
496	  - name: --ksm-metric-labels-allow-list
497	    type: string
498	    short-summary: Comma-separated list of additional Kubernetes label keys that will be used in the resource' labels metric. By default the metric contains only name and namespace labels. To include additional labels provide a list of resource names in their plural form and Kubernetes label keys you would like to allow for them (e.g. '=namespaces=[k8s-label-1,k8s-label-n,...],pods=[app],...)'. A single '*' can be provided per resource instead to allow any labels, but that has severe performance implications (e.g. '=pods=[*]').
499	  - name: --ksm-metric-annotations-allow-list
500	    type: string
501	    short-summary: Comma-separated list of additional Kubernetes label keys that will be used in the resource' labels metric. By default the metric contains only name and namespace labels. To include additional labels provide a list of resource names in their plural form and Kubernetes label keys you would like to allow for them (e.g.'=namespaces=[k8s-label-1,k8s-label-n,...],pods=[app],...)'. A single '*' can be provided per resource instead to allow any labels, but that has severe performance implications (e.g. '=pods=[*]').
502	  - name: --grafana-resource-id
503	    type: string
504	    short-summary: Resource ID of the Azure Managed Grafana Workspace
505	  - name: --enable-windows-recording-rules
506	    type: bool
507	    short-summary: Enable Windows Recording Rules when enabling the Azure Monitor Metrics addon
508	  - name: --nodepool-taints
509	    type: string
510	    short-summary: The node taints for all node pool.
511	  - name: --nodepool-labels
512	    type: string
513	    short-summary: The node labels for all node pool. See https://aka.ms/node-labels for syntax of labels.
514	  - name: --enable-vpa
515	    type: bool
516	    short-summary: Enable vertical pod autoscaler for cluster.
517	  - name: --nodepool-allowed-host-ports
518	    type: string
519	    short-summary: Expose host ports on the node pool. When specified, format should be a space-separated list of ranges with protocol, eg. `80/TCP 443/TCP 4000-5000/TCP`.
520	  - name: --nodepool-asg-ids
521	    type: string
522	    short-summary: The IDs of the application security groups to which the node pool's network interface should belong. When specified, format should be a space-separated list of IDs.
523	  - name: --node-public-ip-tags
524	    type: string
525	    short-summary: The ipTags of the node public IPs.
526	  - name: --crg-id
527	    type: string
528	    short-summary: The crg id used to associate the new cluster with the existed Capacity Reservation Group resource.
529	  - name: --enable-asm --enable-azure-service-mesh
530	    type: bool
531	    short-summary: Enable Azure Service Mesh addon.
532	  - name: --enable-app-routing
533	    type: bool
534	    short-summary: Enable Application Routing addon.
535	  - name: --revision
536	    type: string
537	    short-summary: Azure Service Mesh revision to install.
538	  - name: --enable-cost-analysis
539	    type: bool
540	    short-summary: Enable exporting Kubernetes Namespace and Deployment details to the Cost Analysis views in the Azure portal. For more information see aka.ms/aks/docs/cost-analysis.
541	  - name: --enable-secure-boot
542	    type: bool
543	    short-summary: Enable Secure Boot on all node pools in the cluster. Must use VMSS agent pool type.
544	  - name: --enable-vtpm
545	    type: bool
546	    short-summary: Enable vTPM on all node pools in the cluster. Must use VMSS agent pool type.
547	  - name: --enable-acns
548	    type: bool
549	    short-summary: Enable advanced network functionalities on a cluster. Enabling this will incur additional costs. For non-cilium clusters, acns security will be disabled by default until further notice.
550	  - name: --disable-acns-observability
551	    type: bool
552	    short-summary: Used to disable advanced networking observability features on a clusters when enabling advanced networking features with "--enable-acns".
553	  - name: --disable-acns-security
554	    type: bool
555	    short-summary: Used to disable advanced networking security features on a clusters when enabling advanced networking features with "--enable-acns".
556	  - name: --nrg-lockdown-restriction-level
557	    type: string
558	    short-summary: Restriction level on the managed node resource group.
559	    long-summary: The restriction level of permissions allowed on the cluster's managed node resource group, supported values are Unrestricted, and ReadOnly (recommended ReadOnly).
560	  - name: --if-match
561	    type: string
562	    short-summary: The value provided will be compared to the ETag of the managed cluster, if it matches the operation will proceed. If it does not match, the request will be rejected to prevent accidental overwrites. This must not be specified when creating a new cluster.
563	  - name: --if-none-match
564	    type: string
565	    short-summary: Set to '*' to allow a new cluster to be created, but to prevent updating an existing cluster. Other values will be ignored.
566	  - name: --bootstrap-artifact-source
567	    type: string
568	    short-summary: Configure artifact source when bootstraping the cluster.
569	    long-summary: |
570	        The artifacts include the addon image. Use "Direct" to download artifacts from MCR, "Cache" to downalod artifacts from Azure Container Registry.
571	  - name: --bootstrap-container-registry-resource-id
572	    type: string
573	    short-summary: Configure container registry resource ID. Must use "Cache" as bootstrap artifact source.
574	
575	examples:
576	  - name: Create a Kubernetes cluster with an existing SSH public key.
577	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --ssh-key-value /path/to/publickey
578	  - name: Create a Kubernetes cluster with a specific version.
579	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --kubernetes-version 1.16.9
580	  - name: Create a Kubernetes cluster with a larger node pool.
581	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --node-count 7
582	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with default kubernetes version, default SKU load balancer (Standard) and default vm set type (VirtualMachineScaleSets).
583	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster
584	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with standard SKU load balancer and two AKS created IPs for the load balancer outbound connection usage.
585	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-managed-outbound-ip-count 2
586	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with a standard SKU load balancer, with two outbound AKS managed IPs an idle flow timeout of 5 minutes and 8000 allocated ports per machine
587	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-managed-outbound-ip-count 2 --load-balancer-idle-timeout 5 --load-balancer-outbound-ports 8000
588	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with standard SKU load balancer and use the provided public IPs for the load balancer outbound connection usage.
589	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-outbound-ips <ip-resource-id-1,ip-resource-id-2>
590	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with standard SKU load balancer and use the provided public IP prefixes for the load balancer outbound connection usage.
591	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-outbound-ip-prefixes <ip-prefix-resource-id-1,ip-prefix-resource-id-2>
592	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with a AKS managed NAT gateway, with two outbound AKS managed IPs an idle flow timeout of 4 minutes
593	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --nat-gateway-managed-outbound-ip-count 2 --nat-gateway-idle-timeout 4 --outbound-type managedNATGateway --generate-ssh-keys
594	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with basic SKU load balancer and AvailabilitySet vm set type.
595	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-sku basic --vm-set-type AvailabilitySet
596	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with authorized apiserver IP ranges.
597	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --api-server-authorized-ip-ranges 193.168.1.0/24,194.168.1.0/24,195.168.1.0
598	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster which enables managed identity.
599	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-managed-identity
600	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with userDefinedRouting, standard load balancer SKU and a custom subnet preconfigured with a route table
601	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --outbound-type userDefinedRouting --load-balancer-sku standard --vnet-subnet-id customUserSubnetVnetID
602	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with supporting Windows agent pools.
603	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-sku Standard --network-plugin azure --windows-admin-username azure --windows-admin-password 'replacePassword1234$'
604	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with supporting Windows agent pools with AHUB enabled.
605	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-sku Standard --network-plugin azure --windows-admin-username azure --windows-admin-password 'replacePassword1234$' --enable-ahub
606	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with managed AAD enabled.
607	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-aad --aad-admin-group-object-ids <id-1,id-2> --aad-tenant-id <id>
608	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with server side encryption using your owned key.
609	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --node-osdisk-diskencryptionset-id <disk-encryption-set-resource-id>
610	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with ephemeral OS enabled.
611	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --node-osdisk-type Ephemeral --node-osdisk-size 48
612	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with EncryptionAtHost enabled.
613	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-encryption-at-host
614	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with UltraSSD enabled.
615	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-ultra-ssd
616	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with Azure RBAC enabled.
617	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-aad --enable-azure-rbac
618	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with custom control plane identity and kubelet identity.
619	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --assign-identity <control-plane-identity-resource-id> --assign-kubelet-identity <kubelet-identity-resource-id>
620	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster in the Edge Zone.
621	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --location <location> --kubernetes-version 1.20.7 --edge-zone <edge-zone-name>
622	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with a specific OS SKU
623	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --os-sku Ubuntu
624	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with custom tags
625	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --tags "foo=bar" "baz=qux"
626	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with custom headers
627	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --aks-custom-headers WindowsContainerRuntime=containerd
628	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with FIPS-enabled OS
629	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-fips-image
630	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with enabling Windows gmsa and with setting DNS server in the vnet used by the cluster.
631	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-sku Standard --network-plugin azure --windows-admin-username azure --windows-admin-password 'replacePassword1234$' --enable-windows-gmsa
632	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with enabling Windows gmsa but without setting DNS server in the vnet used by the cluster.
633	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-sku Standard --network-plugin azure --windows-admin-username azure --windows-admin-password 'replacePassword1234$' --enable-windows-gmsa --gmsa-dns-server "10.240.0.4" --gmsa-root-domain-name "contoso.com"
634	  - name: create a kubernetes cluster with a snapshot id.
635	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --kubernetes-version 1.20.9 --snapshot-id "/subscriptions/00000/resourceGroups/AnotherResourceGroup/providers/Microsoft.ContainerService/snapshots/mysnapshot1"
636	  - name: create a kubernetes cluster with support of hostgroup id.
637	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyMC --kubernetes-version 1.20.13 --location westus2 --host-group-id /subscriptions/00000/resourceGroups/AnotherResourceGroup/providers/Microsoft.ContainerService/hostGroups/myHostGroup --node-vm-size VMSize --enable-managed-identity --assign-identity <user_assigned_identity_resource_id>
638	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with no CNI installed.
639	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --network-plugin none
640	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with KEDA workload autoscaler enabled.
641	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-keda
642	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with the Azure Monitor managed service for Prometheus integration enabled.
643	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-azure-monitor-metrics
644	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with vertical pod autoscaler enaled.
645	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-vpa
646	  - name: create a kubernetes cluster with a Capacity Reservation Group(CRG) ID.
647	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyMC --kubernetes-version 1.20.9 --node-vm-size VMSize --assign-identity "subscriptions/SubID/resourceGroups/RGName/providers/Microsoft.ManagedIdentity/userAssignedIdentities/myID" --enable-managed-identity --crg-id "subscriptions/SubID/resourceGroups/RGName/providers/Microsoft.ContainerService/CapacityReservationGroups/MyCRGID"
648	  - name: Create a kubernetes cluster with Azure Service Mesh enabled.
649	    text: az aks create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-azure-service-mesh
650	"""

652	helps['aks update'] = """
653	type: command
654	short-summary: Update a managed Kubernetes cluster. When called with no optional arguments this attempts to move the cluster to its goal state without changing the current cluster configuration. This can be used to move out of a non succeeded state.
655	parameters:
656	  - name: --enable-cluster-autoscaler -e
657	    type: bool
658	    short-summary: Enable cluster autoscaler.
659	  - name: --disable-cluster-autoscaler -d
660	    type: bool
661	    short-summary: Disable cluster autoscaler.
662	  - name: --update-cluster-autoscaler -u
663	    type: bool
664	    short-summary: Update min-count or max-count for cluster autoscaler.
665	  - name: --min-count
666	    type: int
667	    short-summary: Minimum nodes count used for autoscaler, when "--enable-cluster-autoscaler" specified. Please specify the value in the range of [1, 1000]
668	  - name: --max-count
669	    type: int
670	    short-summary: Maximum nodes count used for autoscaler, when "--enable-cluster-autoscaler" specified. Please specify the value in the range of [1, 1000]
671	  - name: --tier
672	    type: string
673	    short-summary: Specify SKU tier for managed clusters. '--tier standard' enables a standard managed cluster service with a financially backed SLA. '--tier free' changes a standard managed cluster to a free one.
674	  - name: --ip-families
675	    type: string
676	    short-summary: A comma-separated list of IP versions to use for cluster networking.
677	    long-summary: Each IP version should be in the format IPvN. For example, IPv4.
678	  - name: --network-plugin
679	    type: string
680	    short-summary: The Kubernetes network plugin to use.
681	    long-summary: Specify "azure" along with --network-plugin-mode=overlay to update a cluster to use Azure CNI Overlay. For more information see https://aka.ms/aks/azure-cni-overlay
682	  - name: --network-plugin-mode
683	    type: string
684	    short-summary: Update the mode of a network plugin to migrate to a different pod networking setup.
685	  - name: --network-policy
686	    type: string
687	    short-summary: Update Network Policy Engine.
688	    long-summary: |
689	        Azure provides three Network Policy Engines for enforcing network policies. The following values can be specified:
690	          - "azure" for Azure Network Policy Manager,
691	          - "cilium" for Azure CNI Powered by Cilium,
692	          - "calico" for open-source network and network security solution founded by Tigera,
693	          - "none" to uninstall Network Policy Engine (Azure Network Policy Manager or Calico).
694	        Defaults to "none" (network policy disabled).
695	  - name: --pod-cidr
696	    type: string
697	    short-summary: Update the pod CIDR for a cluster. Used when updating a cluster from Azure CNI to Azure CNI Overlay.
698	  - name: --network-dataplane
699	    type: string
700	    short-summary: The network dataplane to use.
701	    long-summary: |
702	        Network dataplane used in the Kubernetes cluster.
703	        Specify "azure" to use the Azure dataplane (default) or "cilium" to enable Cilium dataplane.
704	  - name: --load-balancer-managed-outbound-ip-count
705	    type: int
706	    short-summary: Load balancer managed outbound IP count.
707	    long-summary: Desired number of managed outbound IPs for load balancer outbound connection. Valid for Standard SKU load balancer cluster only. If the new value is greater than the original value, new additional outbound IPs will be created. If the value is less than the original value, existing outbound IPs will be deleted and outbound connections may fail due to configuration update.
708	  - name: --load-balancer-managed-outbound-ipv6-count
709	    type: int
710	    short-summary: Load balancer managed outbound IPv6 IP count.
711	    long-summary: Desired number of managed outbound IPv6 IPs for load balancer outbound connection. Valid for dual-stack (--ip-families IPv4,IPv6) only.
712	  - name: --load-balancer-outbound-ips
713	    type: string
714	    short-summary: Load balancer outbound IP resource IDs.
715	    long-summary: Comma-separated public IP resource IDs for load balancer outbound connection. Valid for Standard SKU load balancer cluster only.
716	  - name: --load-balancer-outbound-ip-prefixes
717	    type: string
718	    short-summary: Load balancer outbound IP prefix resource IDs.
719	    long-summary: Comma-separated public IP prefix resource IDs for load balancer outbound connection. Valid for Standard SKU load balancer cluster only.
720	  - name: --load-balancer-outbound-ports
721	    type: int
722	    short-summary: Load balancer outbound allocated ports.
723	    long-summary: Desired static number of outbound ports per VM in the load balancer backend pool. By default, set to 0 which uses the default allocation based on the number of VMs.
724	  - name: --load-balancer-idle-timeout
725	    type: int
726	    short-summary: Load balancer idle timeout in minutes.
727	    long-summary: Desired idle timeout for load balancer outbound flows, default is 30 minutes. Please specify a value in the range of [4, 100].
728	  - name: --load-balancer-backend-pool-type
729	    type: string
730	    short-summary: Load balancer backend pool type.
731	    long-summary: Define the LoadBalancer backend pool type of managed inbound backend pool. The nodeIP means the VMs will be attached to the LoadBalancer by adding its private IP address to the backend pool. The nodeIPConfiguration means the VMs will be attached to the LoadBalancer by referencing the backend pool ID in the VM's NIC.
732	  - name: --nat-gateway-managed-outbound-ip-count
733	    type: int
734	    short-summary: NAT gateway managed outbound IP count.
735	    long-summary: Desired number of managed outbound IPs for NAT gateway outbound connection. Please specify a value in the range of [1, 16]. Valid for Standard SKU load balancer cluster with managedNATGateway outbound type only.
736	  - name: --nat-gateway-idle-timeout
737	    type: int
738	    short-summary: NAT gateway idle timeout in minutes.
739	    long-summary: Desired idle timeout for NAT gateway outbound flows, default is 4 minutes. Please specify a value in the range of [4, 120]. Valid for Standard SKU load balancer cluster with managedNATGateway outbound type only.
740	  - name: --outbound-type
741	    type: string
742	    short-summary: How outbound traffic will be configured for a cluster.
743	    long-summary: This option will change the way how the outbound connections are managed in the AKS cluster. Available options are loadbalancer, managedNATGateway, userAssignedNATGateway, userDefinedRouting and none. For custom vnet, loadbalancer, userAssignedNATGateway and userDefinedRouting are supported. For aks managed vnet, loadbalancer, managedNATGateway and userDefinedRouting are supported.

1010	examples:
1011	  - name: Reconcile the cluster back to its current state.
1012	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster
1013	  - name: Update a kubernetes cluster with standard SKU load balancer to use two AKS created IPs for the load balancer outbound connection usage.
1014	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-managed-outbound-ip-count 2
1015	  - name: Update a kubernetes cluster with standard SKU load balancer to use the provided public IPs for the load balancer outbound connection usage.
1016	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-outbound-ips <ip-resource-id-1,ip-resource-id-2>
1017	  - name: Update a kubernetes cluster with a standard SKU load balancer, with two outbound AKS managed IPs an idle flow timeout of 5 minutes and 8000 allocated ports per machine
1018	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-managed-outbound-ip-count 2 --load-balancer-idle-timeout 5 --load-balancer-outbound-ports 8000
1019	  - name: Update a kubernetes cluster with standard SKU load balancer to use the provided public IP prefixes for the load balancer outbound connection usage.
1020	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --load-balancer-outbound-ip-prefixes <ip-prefix-resource-id-1,ip-prefix-resource-id-2>
1021	  - name: Update a kubernetes cluster of managedNATGateway outbound type with two outbound AKS managed IPs an idle flow timeout of 4 minutes
1022	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --nat-gateway-managed-outbound-ip-count 2 --nat-gateway-idle-timeout 4
1023	  - name: Attach AKS cluster to ACR by name "acrName"
1024	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --attach-acr acrName
1025	  - name: Update a kubernetes cluster with authorized apiserver ip ranges.
1026	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --api-server-authorized-ip-ranges 193.168.1.0/24,194.168.1.0/24
1027	  - name: Disable authorized apiserver ip ranges feature for a kubernetes cluster.
1028	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --api-server-authorized-ip-ranges ""
1029	  - name: Restrict apiserver traffic in a kubernetes cluster to agentpool nodes.
1030	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --api-server-authorized-ip-ranges 0.0.0.0/32
1031	  - name: Update a AKS-managed AAD cluster with tenant ID or admin group object IDs.
1032	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --aad-admin-group-object-ids <id-1,id-2> --aad-tenant-id <id>
1033	  - name: Migrate a AKS AAD-Integrated cluster or a non-AAD cluster to a AKS-managed AAD cluster.
1034	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-aad --aad-admin-group-object-ids <id-1,id-2> --aad-tenant-id <id>
1035	  - name: Enable Azure Hybrid User Benefits featture for a kubernetes cluster.
1036	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-ahub
1037	  - name: Disable Azure Hybrid User Benefits featture for a kubernetes cluster.
1038	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --disable-ahub
1039	  - name: Update Windows password of a kubernetes cluster
1040	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCLuster --windows-admin-password "Repl@cePassw0rd12345678"
1041	  - name: Update the cluster to use system assigned managed identity in control plane.
1042	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-managed-identity
1043	  - name: Update the cluster to use user assigned managed identity in control plane.
1044	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-managed-identity --assign-identity <user_assigned_identity_resource_id>
1045	  - name: Update a non managed AAD AKS cluster to use Azure RBAC
1046	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-aad --enable-azure-rbac
1047	  - name: Update a managed AAD AKS cluster to use Azure RBAC
1048	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-azure-rbac
1049	  - name: Disable Azure RBAC in a managed AAD AKS cluster
1050	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --disable-azure-rbac
1051	  - name: Update the tags of a kubernetes cluster
1052	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCLuster --tags "foo=bar" "baz=qux"
1053	  - name: Update a kubernetes cluster with custom headers
1054	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --aks-custom-headers WindowsContainerRuntime=containerd,AKSHTTPCustomFeatures=Microsoft.ContainerService/CustomNodeConfigPreview
1055	  - name: Enable Windows gmsa for a kubernetes cluster with setting DNS server in the vnet used by the cluster.
1056	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-windows-gmsa
1057	  - name: Enable Windows gmsa for a kubernetes cluster without setting DNS server in the vnet used by the cluster.
1058	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-windows-gmsa --gmsa-dns-server "10.240.0.4" --gmsa-root-domain-name "contoso.com"
1059	  - name: Disable Windows gmsa for a kubernetes cluster.
1060	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --disable-windows-gmsa
1061	  - name: Enable KEDA workload autoscaler for an existing kubernetes cluster.
1062	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --enable-keda
1063	  - name: Disable KEDA workload autoscaler for an existing kubernetes cluster.
1064	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCluster --disable-keda
1065	  - name: Enable VPA(Vertical Pod Autoscaler) for an existing kubernetes cluster.
1066	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCLuster --enable-vpa
1067	  - name: Disable VPA(Vertical Pod Autoscaler) for an existing kubernetes cluster.
1068	    text: az aks update -g MyResourceGroup -n MyManagedCLuster --disable-vpa

1522	type: command
1523	short-summary: Add a node pool to the managed Kubernetes cluster.
1524	parameters:
1525	  - name: --node-vm-size -s
1526	    type: string
1527	    short-summary: Size of Virtual Machines to create as Kubernetes nodes.
1528	  - name: --node-count -c
1529	    type: int
1530	    short-summary: Number of nodes in the Kubernetes agent pool. After creating a cluster, you can change the size of its node pool with `az aks scale`.
1531	  - name: --kubernetes-version -k
1532	    type: string
1533	    short-summary: Version of Kubernetes to use for creating the cluster, such as "1.16.9".
1534	    populator-commands:

1536	  - name: --node-osdisk-size
1537	    type: int
1538	    short-summary: Size in GiB of the OS disk for each node in the agent pool. Minimum 30 GiB.
1539	  - name: --node-osdisk-type
1540	    type: string
1541	    short-summary: OS disk type to be used for machines in a given agent pool. Defaults to 'Ephemeral' when possible in conjunction with VM size and OS disk size. May not be changed for this pool after creation. ('Ephemeral' or 'Managed')
1542	  - name: --max-pods -m
1543	    type: int
1544	    short-summary: The maximum number of pods deployable to a node.
1545	    long-summary: If not specified, defaults based on network-plugin. 30 for "azure", 110 for "kubenet", or 250 for "none".
1546	  - name: --zones -z
1547	    type: string array
1548	    short-summary: Availability zones where agent nodes will be placed. Also, to install agent nodes to more than one zone you need to pass zone numbers separated by blanks.  For example -  To have all 3 zones, you are expected to enter `--zones 1 2 3`
1549	  - name: --enable-node-public-ip

1558	  - name: --pod-subnet-id

1561	  - name: --ppg

1563	    short-summary: The ID of a PPG.
1564	  - name: --os-type

1571	    type: bool
1572	    short-summary: Enable cluster autoscaler.
1573	  - name: --min-count

1576	  - name: --max-count
1577	    type: int
1578	    short-summary: Maximum nodes count used for autoscaler, when "--enable-cluster-autoscaler" specified. Please specify the value in the range of [0, 1000] for user nodepool, and [1,1000] for system nodepool.
1579	  - name: --scale-down-mode
1580	    type: string
1581	    short-summary: "Describe how VMs are added to or removed from nodepools."

1585	  - name: --labels
1586	    type: string
1587	    short-summary: The node labels for the node pool. See https://aka.ms/node-labels for syntax of labels.
1588	  - name: --mode
1589	    type: string
1590	    short-summary: The mode for a node pool which defines a node pool's primary function. If set as "System", AKS prefers system pods scheduling to node pools with mode `System`. Learn more at https://aka.ms/aks/nodepool/mode.
1591	  - name: --priority
1592	    type: string
1593	    short-summary: The priority of the node pool.
1594	  - name: --eviction-policy
1595	    type: string
1596	    short-summary: The eviction policy of the Spot node pool. It can only be set when --priority is Spot.

1598	    type: float
1599	    short-summary: It can only be set when --priority is Spot. Specify the maximum price you are willing to pay in US Dollars. Possible values are any decimal value greater than zero or -1 which indicates default price to be up-to on-demand. It can only include up to 5 decimal places.
1600	  - name: --max-surge
1601	    type: string
1602	    short-summary: Extra nodes used to speed upgrade. When specified, it represents the number or percent used, eg. 5 or 33%
1603	  - name: --drain-timeout
1604	    type: int
1605	    short-summary: When nodes are drain how many minutes to wait for all pods to be evicted
1606	  - name: --node-soak-duration
1607	    type: int
1608	    short-summary: The amount of time (in minutes) to wait after draining a node and before reimaging it and moving on to next node.
1609	  - name: --enable-encryption-at-host
1610	    type: bool
1611	    short-summary: Enable EncryptionAtHost, default value is false.
1612	  - name: --enable-ultra-ssd
1613	    type: bool
1614	    short-summary: Enable UltraSSD, default value is false.
1615	  - name: --enable-fips-image
1616	    type: bool
1617	    short-summary: Use FIPS-enabled OS on agent nodes.
1618	  - name: --snapshot-id
1619	    type: string
1620	    short-summary: The source snapshot id used to create this nodepool.
1621	  - name: --aks-custom-headers
1622	    type: string
1623	    short-summary: Comma-separated key-value pairs to specify custom headers.

1635	    short-summary: The fully qualified dedicated host group id used to provision agent node pool.
1636	  - name: --gpu-instance-profile
1637	    type: string
1638	    short-summary: GPU instance profile to partition multi-gpu Nvidia GPUs.
1639	  - name: --allowed-host-ports
1640	    type: string
1641	    short-summary: Expose host ports on the node pool. When specified, format should be a space-separated list of ranges with protocol, eg. `80/TCP 443/TCP 4000-5000/TCP`.
1642	  - name: --asg-ids
1643	    type: string
1644	    short-summary: The IDs of the application security groups to which the node pool's network interface should belong. When specified, format should be a space-separated list of IDs.
1645	  - name: --node-public-ip-tags
1646	    type: string
1647	    short-summary: The ipTags of the node public IPs.
1648	  - name: --crg-id
1649	    type: string
1650	    short-summary: The crg id used to associate the new nodepool with the existed Capacity Reservation Group resource.
1651	  - name: --disable-windows-outbound-nat
1652	    type: bool
1653	    short-summary: Disable Windows OutboundNAT on Windows agent node pool.
1654	  - name: --enable-secure-boot
1655	    type: bool
1656	    short-summary: Enable Secure Boot on agent node pool. Must use VMSS agent pool type.
1657	  - name: --enable-vtpm
1658	    type: bool
1659	    short-summary: Enable vTPM on agent node pool. Must use VMSS agent pool type.
1660	  - name: --if-match
1661	    type: string
1662	    short-summary: The value provided will be compared to the ETag of the agentpool, if it matches the operation will proceed. If it does not match, the request will be rejected to prevent accidental overwrites. This must not be specified when creating a new agentpool.
1663	  - name: --if-none-match
1664	    type: string
1665	    short-summary: Set to '*' to allow a new agentpool to be created, but to prevent updating an existing agentpool. Other values will be ignored.
1666	
1667	examples:
1668	  - name: Create a nodepool in an existing AKS cluster with ephemeral os enabled.
1669	    text: az aks nodepool add -g MyResourceGroup -n nodepool1 --cluster-name MyManagedCluster --node-osdisk-type Ephemeral --node-osdisk-size 48
1670	  - name: Create a nodepool with EncryptionAtHost enabled.
1671	    text: az aks nodepool add -g MyResourceGroup -n nodepool1 --cluster-name MyManagedCluster --enable-encryption-at-host
1672	  - name: Create a nodepool with UltraSSD enabled.
1673	    text: az aks nodepool add -g MyResourceGroup -n nodepool1 --cluster-name MyManagedCluster --enable-ultra-ssd
1674	  - name: Create a nodepool cluster with a specific OS SKU
1675	    text: az aks nodepool add -g MyResourceGroup -n nodepool1 --cluster-name MyManagedCluster --os-sku Ubuntu
1676	  - name: Create a nodepool with FIPS-enabled OS
1677	    text: az aks nodepool add -g MyResourceGroup -n nodepool1 --cluster-name MyManagedCluster --enable-fips-image
1678	  - name: create a kubernetes cluster with a snapshot id.
1679	    text: az aks nodepool add -g MyResourceGroup -n nodepool1 --cluster-name MyManagedCluster --kubernetes-version 1.20.9 --snapshot-id "/subscriptions/00000/resourceGroups/AnotherResourceGroup/providers/Microsoft.ContainerService/snapshots/mysnapshot1"
1680	  - name: create a nodepool in an existing AKS cluster with host group id
1681	    text: az aks nodepool add -g MyResourceGroup -n MyNodePool --cluster-name MyMC --host-group-id /subscriptions/00000/resourceGroups/AnotherResourceGroup/providers/Microsoft.ContainerService/hostGroups/myHostGroup --node-vm-size VMSize
1682	  - name: create a nodepool with a Capacity Reservation Group(CRG) ID.
1683	    text: az aks nodepool add -g MyResourceGroup -n MyNodePool --cluster-name MyMC --node-vm-size VMSize --crg-id "/subscriptions/SubID/resourceGroups/ResourceGroupName/providers/Microsoft.ContainerService/CapacityReservationGroups/MyCRGID"

1730	type: command
1731	short-summary: Update a node pool properties.
1732	long-summary: Update a node pool to enable/disable cluster-autoscaler or change min-count or max-count. When called with no optional arguments this attempts to move the node pool to its goal state without changing the current node pool configuration. This can be used to move out of a non succeeded state.
1733	parameters:
1734	  - name: --enable-cluster-autoscaler -e
1735	    type: bool
1736	    short-summary: Enable cluster autoscaler.
1737	  - name: --disable-cluster-autoscaler -d

1745	    short-summary: Minimum nodes count used for autoscaler, when "--enable-cluster-autoscaler" specified. Please specify the value in the range of [0, 1000] for user nodepool, and [1,1000] for system nodepool.
1746	  - name: --max-count
1747	    type: int

697	    zip file with the following content '[config] SCM_DO_BUILD_DURING_DEPLOYMENT = true',
698	    to enable Kudu detection logic and build script generation process.
699	    See https://github.com/projectkudu/kudu/wiki/Configurable-settings#enabledisable-build-actions-preview.
700	    Alternately the setting can be enabled using the az functionapp config appsettings set command.
701	examples:
702	  - name: Perform deployment by using zip file content.
703	    text: >
704	        az functionapp deployment source config-zip \\
705	            -g {myRG} -n {myAppName} \\
706	            --src {zipFilePathLocation}
707	"""
708

25	long-summary: This article lists the Azure CLI commands for Azure Cognitive Services account and subscription management only. Refer to the documentation at https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/cognitive-services/ for individual services to learn how to use the APIs and supported SDKs.

27	  - name: --kind
28	    populator-commands:

30	  - name: --sku --sku-name

32	      - az cognitiveservices account list-skus
33	examples:
34	  - name: Create an S0 face API Cognitive Services account in West Europe without confirmation required.
35	    text: az cognitiveservices account create -n myresource -g myResourceGroup --kind Face --sku S0 -l WestEurope --yes
36	  - name: Manage Azure Cognitive Services accounts. (autogenerated)
37	    text: az cognitiveservices account create --kind Face --location WestEurope --name myresource --resource-group myResourceGroup --sku S0 --subscription MySubscription --yes
38	    crafted: true
39	  - name: Create a Text Analytics Cognitive Services account in West Europe without confirmation required and use customer owned storage.
40	    text: |
41	        az cognitiveservices account create -n myresource -g myResourceGroup --assign-identity --kind TextAnalytics --sku S -l WestEurope --yes

43	            {
44	              "resourceId": "/subscriptions/xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx/resourceGroups/myResourceGroup/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/myStorageAccount"
45	            }
46	          ]'
47	  - name: Create a Text Analytics Cognitive Services account in West Europe without confirmation required and user Customer-managed encryption.

49	        az cognitiveservices account create -n myresource -g myResourceGroup --assign-identity --kind TextAnalytics --sku S -l WestEurope --yes

25	type: command
26	short-summary: Create a container group.
27	examples:
28	  - name: Create a container in a container group with 1 core and 1Gb of memory.
29	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --cpu 1 --memory 1
30	  - name: Create a container in a container group that runs Windows, with 2 cores and 3.5Gb of memory.
31	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name mywinapp --image winappimage:latest --os-type Windows --cpu 2 --memory 3.5
32	  - name: Create a container in a container group with public IP address, ports and DNS name label.
33	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --ports 80 443 --dns-name-label contoso
34	  - name: Create a container in a container group that invokes a script upon start.
35	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --command-line "/bin/sh -c '/path to/myscript.sh'"
36	  - name: Create a container in a container group that runs a command and stop the container afterwards.
37	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --command-line "echo hello" --restart-policy Never
38	  - name: Create a container in a container group with environment variables.
39	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --environment-variables key1=value1 key2=value2
40	  - name: Create a container in a container group using container image from Azure Container Registry.
41	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myAcrRegistry.azurecr.io/myimage:latest --registry-password password
42	  - name: Create a container in a container group that mounts an Azure File share as volume.
43	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --command-line "cat /mnt/azfile/myfile" --azure-file-volume-share-name myshare --azure-file-volume-account-name mystorageaccount --azure-file-volume-account-key mystoragekey --azure-file-volume-mount-path /mnt/azfile
44	  - name: Create a container in a container group that mounts a git repo as volume.
45	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --command-line "cat /mnt/gitrepo" --gitrepo-url https://github.com/user/myrepo.git --gitrepo-dir ./dir1 --gitrepo-mount-path /mnt/gitrepo
46	  - name: Create a container in a container group using a yaml file.
47	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup -f containerGroup.yaml
48	  - name: Create a container group using Log Analytics from a workspace name.
49	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --log-analytics-workspace myworkspace
50	  - name: Create a container group with a system assigned identity.
51	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --assign-identity
52	  - name: Create a container group with a system assigned identity. The group will have a 'Contributor' role with access to a storage account.
53	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --assign-identity --scope /subscriptions/99999999-1bf0-4dda-aec3-cb9272f09590/MyResourceGroup/myRG/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/storage1
54	  - name: Create a container group with a user assigned identity.
55	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --assign-identity  /subscriptions/mySubscriptionId/resourcegroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.ManagedIdentity/userAssignedIdentities/myID
56	  - name: Create a container group with both system and user assigned identity.
57	    text: az container create -g MyResourceGroup --name myapp --image myimage:latest --assign-identity [system] /subscriptions/mySubscriptionId/resourcegroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.ManagedIdentity/userAssignedIdentities/myID

153	helps['eventgrid domain topic event-subscription create'] = """
154	type: command
155	short-summary: Create a new event subscription for a domain topic
156	parameters:
157	  - name: --advanced-filter
158	    short-summary: An advanced filter enables filtering of events based on a specific event property.
159	    long-summary: |
160	        Usage:                     --advanced-filter KEY[.INNERKEY] FILTEROPERATOR VALUE [VALUE ...]
161	        StringIn:                  --advanced-filter data.Color StringIn Blue Red Orange Yellow
162	        StringNotIn:               --advanced-filter data.Color StringNotIn Blue Red Orange Yellow
163	        StringContains:            --advanced-filter subject StringContains Blue Red
164	        StringNotContains:         --advanced-filter subject StringNotContains Blue Red
165	        StringBeginsWith:          --advanced-filter subject StringBeginsWith Blue Red
166	        StringNotBeginsWith:       --advanced-filter subject StringNotBeginsWith Blue Red
167	        StringEndsWith:            --advanced-filter subject StringEndsWith img png jpg
168	        StringNotEndsWith:         --advanced-filter subject StringNotEndsWith img png jpg
169	        NumberIn:                  --advanced-filter data.property1 NumberIn 5 10 20
170	        NumberInRange              --advanced-filter data.property1 NumberInRange 5,10 20,30 40,50
171	        NumberNotIn:               --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberNotIn 100 200 300
172	        NumberNotInRange:          --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberNotInRange 100,110 200,210 300,310
173	        NumberLessThan:            --advanced-filter data.property3 NumberLessThan 100
174	        NumberLessThanOrEquals:    --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberLessThanOrEquals 100
175	        NumberGreaterThan:         --advanced-filter data.property3 NumberGreaterThan 100
176	        NumberGreaterThanOrEquals: --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberGreaterThanOrEquals 100
177	        BoolEquals:                --advanced-filter data.property3 BoolEquals true
178	        IsNullOrUndefined:         --advanced-filter data.property3 IsNullOrUndefined
179	        IsNotNull:                 --advanced-filter data.property3 IsNotNull
180	        Multiple advanced filters can be specified by using more than one `--advanced-filter` argument.
181	  - name: --deadletter-endpoint
182	    short-summary: The Azure resource ID of an Azure Storage blob container destination where EventGrid should deadletter undeliverable events for this event subscription.
183	    long-summary: |
184	        Example: --deadletter-endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/rg1/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/sa1/blobServices/default/containers/containerName
185	  - name: --endpoint-type
186	    short-summary: The type of the destination endpoint.
187	  - name: --delivery-attribute-mapping -d
188	    short-summary: Add delivery attribute mapping to send additional information via HTTP headers when delivering events. This attribute is valid for all destination types except StorageQueue. Multiple attributes can be specified by using more than one `--delivery-attribute-mapping` argument.
189	    long-summary: |
190	        Usage:                        --delivery-attribute-mapping attribute-name attribute-type attribute-value [attribute-is-secret]
191	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue
192	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue false
193	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue true
194	        Dynamic Attribute Mapping:    --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue
195	        Both Static and Dynamic:      --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue --delivery-attribute-mapping somename2 static somevalue
196	examples:
197	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic, using default filters.
198	    text: |
199	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription create --name es1 \\
200	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
201	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
202	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic, with a filter specifying a subject prefix.
203	    text: |
204	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription create --name es4 \\
205	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
206	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code \\
207	            --subject-begins-with mysubject_prefix
208	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic, using default filters, and CloudEvent V 1.0 as the delivery schema.
209	    text: |
210	      az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription create -n es2 \\
211	          -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
212	          --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code \\
213	          --event-delivery-schema cloudeventschemav1_0
214	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic, with a deadletter destination and custom retry policy of maximum 10 delivery attempts and an Event TTL of 2 hours (whichever happens earlier) and expiration date.
215	    text: |
216	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription create --name es2 \\
217	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
218	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code \\
219	            --deadletter-endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/TestRG/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/s2/blobServices/default/containers/blobcontainer1 \\
220	            --max-delivery-attempts 10 --event-ttl 120 --expiration-date "2022-10-31"
221	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic, using Azure Active Directory enabled Webhook as a destination.
222	    text: |
223	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription create --name es1 \\
224	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
225	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
226	            --azure-active-directory-tenant-id azureactivedirectorytenantid
227	            --azure-active-directory-application-id-or-uri azureactivedirectoryapplicationidoruri
228	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic, using Azure Function as destination.
229	    text: |
230	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription create -n es1 \\
231	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
232	            --endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/Microsoft.Web/sites/{functionappname}/functions/{functionname} --endpoint-type azurefunction
233	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic using Storage Queue as destination with a ttl of 5 mins
234	    text: |
235	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription create -n es1 \\
236	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
237	            --endpoint-type storagequeue \\
238	            --endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/TestRG/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/sa1/queueservices/default/queues/q1 \\
239	            --storage-queue-msg-ttl 300
240	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic and enable advanced filtering on arrays
241	    text: |
242	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription create -n es1 \\
243	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
244	            --endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/Microsoft.Web/sites/{functionappname}/functions/{functionname} --endpoint-type azurefunction \\
245	            --enable-advanced-filtering-on-arrays true
246	
247	"""

295	        StringNotContains:         --advanced-filter subject StringNotContains Blue Red

300	        NumberIn:                  --advanced-filter data.property1 NumberIn 5 10 20
301	        NumberInRange              --advanced-filter data.property1 NumberInRange 5,10 20,30 40,50
302	        NumberNotIn:               --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberNotIn 100 200 300
303	        NumberNotInRange:          --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberNotInRange 100,110 200,210 300,310
304	        NumberLessThan:            --advanced-filter data.property3 NumberLessThan 100
305	        NumberLessThanOrEquals:    --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberLessThanOrEquals 100
306	        NumberGreaterThan:         --advanced-filter data.property3 NumberGreaterThan 100
307	        NumberGreaterThanOrEquals: --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberGreaterThanOrEquals 100
308	        BoolEquals:                --advanced-filter data.property3 BoolEquals true
309	        IsNullOrUndefined:         --advanced-filter data.property3 IsNullOrUndefined
310	        IsNotNull:                 --advanced-filter data.property3 IsNotNull
311	        Multiple advanced filters can be specified by using more than one `--advanced-filter` argument.
312	  - name: --delivery-attribute-mapping -d
313	    short-summary: Add delivery attribute mapping to send additional information via HTTP headers when delivering events. This attribute is valid for all destination types except StorageQueue. Multiple attributes can be specified by using more than one `--delivery-attribute-mapping` argument.
314	    long-summary: |
315	        Usage:                        --delivery-attribute-mapping attribute-name attribute-type attribute-value [attribute-is-secret]
316	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue
317	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue false
318	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue true
319	        Dynamic Attribute Mapping:    --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue
320	        Both Static and Dynamic:      --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue --delivery-attribute-mapping somename2 static somevalue
321	examples:
322	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic to specify a new endpoint.
323	    text: |

325	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
326	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic to specify a new subject-ends-with filter.
327	    text: |
328	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription update --name es2 \\
329	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
330	            --subject-ends-with .jpg
331	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic to specify a new endpoint and a new subject-ends-with filter a new list of included event types.
332	    text: |
333	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription update --name es3 \\
334	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
335	            --subject-ends-with .png \\
336	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
337	            --included-event-types Microsoft.Storage.BlobCreated Microsoft.Storage.BlobDeleted
338	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Azure Event Grid domain topic, to include a deadletter destination.
339	    text: |
340	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription update --name es2 \\
341	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
342	            --deadletter-endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/TestRG/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/sa1/blobServices/default/containers/blobcontainer1
343	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Azure Event Grid domain topic, using advanced filters.
344	    text: |
345	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription update --name es3 \\
346	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\
347	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
348	            --advanced-filter data.blobType StringIn BlockBlob
349	            --advanced-filter data.url StringBeginsWith https://myaccount.blob.core.windows.net
350	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Event Grid domain topic with Storage Queue as destination with ttl of 5 mins
351	    text: |
352	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription update -n es1 \\
353	            -g rg1 --domain-name domain1 --domain-topic-name topic1 \\

357	        az eventgrid domain topic event-subscription update -n es1 \\

991	            --azure-active-directory-tenant-id azureactivedirectorytenantid
992	            --azure-active-directory-application-id-or-uri azureactivedirectoryapplicationidoruri
993	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid system topic, using Azure Function as destination.
994	    text: |
995	        az eventgrid system-topic event-subscription create -n es1 \\
996	            -g rg1 --system-topic-name systemtopic1 \\
997	            --endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/Microsoft.Web/sites/{functionappname}/functions/{functionname} --endpoint-type azurefunction
998	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid system topic using Storage Queue as destination with a ttl of 5 mins
999	    text: |
1000	        az eventgrid system-topic event-subscription create -n es1 \\
1001	            -g rg1 --system-topic-name systemtopic1 \\
1002	            --endpoint-type storagequeue \\
1003	            --endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/TestRG/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/sa1/queueservices/default/queues/q1 \\
1004	            --storage-queue-msg-ttl 300
1005	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid system topic and enable advanced filtering on arrays
1006	    text: |
1007	        az eventgrid system-topic event-subscription create -n es1 \\
1008	            -g rg1 --system-topic-name systemtopic1 \\

1047	helps['eventgrid system-topic event-subscription update'] = """
1048	type: command
1049	short-summary: Update an event subscription of a system topic.
1050	parameters:
1051	  - name: --endpoint-type
1052	    short-summary: The type of the destination endpoint.
1053	  - name: --advanced-filter
1054	    short-summary: An advanced filter enables filtering of events based on a specific event property.
1055	    long-summary: |
1056	        Usage:                     --advanced-filter KEY[.INNERKEY] FILTEROPERATOR VALUE [VALUE ...]
1057	        StringIn:                  --advanced-filter data.Color StringIn Blue Red Orange Yellow
1058	        StringNotIn:               --advanced-filter data.Color StringNotIn Blue Red Orange Yellow
1059	        StringContains:            --advanced-filter subject StringContains Blue Red
1060	        StringNotContains:         --advanced-filter subject StringNotContains Blue Red
1061	        StringBeginsWith:          --advanced-filter subject StringBeginsWith Blue Red
1062	        StringNotBeginsWith:       --advanced-filter subject StringNotBeginsWith Blue Red
1063	        StringEndsWith:            --advanced-filter subject StringEndsWith img png jpg
1064	        StringNotEndsWith:         --advanced-filter subject StringNotEndsWith img png jpg
1065	        NumberIn:                  --advanced-filter data.property1 NumberIn 5 10 20
1066	        NumberInRange              --advanced-filter data.property1 NumberInRange 5,10 20,30 40,50
1067	        NumberNotIn:               --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberNotIn 100 200 300
1068	        NumberNotInRange:          --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberNotInRange 100,110 200,210 300,310
1069	        NumberLessThan:            --advanced-filter data.property3 NumberLessThan 100
1070	        NumberLessThanOrEquals:    --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberLessThanOrEquals 100
1071	        NumberGreaterThan:         --advanced-filter data.property3 NumberGreaterThan 100
1072	        NumberGreaterThanOrEquals: --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberGreaterThanOrEquals 100
1073	        BoolEquals:                --advanced-filter data.property3 BoolEquals true
1074	        IsNullOrUndefined:         --advanced-filter data.property3 IsNullOrUndefined
1075	        IsNotNull:                 --advanced-filter data.property3 IsNotNull
1076	        Multiple advanced filters can be specified by using more than one `--advanced-filter` argument.
1077	  - name: --delivery-attribute-mapping
1078	    short-summary: Add delivery attribute mapping to send additional information via HTTP headers when delivering events. This attribute is valid for all destination types except StorageQueue. Multiple attributes can be specified by using more than one `--delivery-attribute-mapping` argument.
1079	    long-summary: |
1080	        Usage:                        --delivery-attribute-mapping attribute-name attribute-type attribute-value [attribute-is-secret]
1081	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue
1082	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue false
1083	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue true
1084	        Dynamic Attribute Mapping:    --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue
1085	        Both Static and Dynamic:      --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue --delivery-attribute-mapping somename2 static somevalue
1086	examples:
1087	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Event Grid system topic to specify a new endpoint.
1088	    text: |
1089	        az eventgrid system-topic event-subscription update --name es1 \\
1090	            -g rg1 --system-topic-name systemtopic1 --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
1091	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Event Grid system topic to specify a new subject-ends-with filter.
1092	    text: |
1093	        az eventgrid system-topic event-subscription update --name es2 \\
1094	            -g rg1 --system-topic-name systemtopic1 \\
1095	            --subject-ends-with .jpg
1096	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Event Grid system topic to specify a new endpoint and a new subject-ends-with filter a new list of included event types.
1097	    text: |
1098	        az eventgrid system-topic event-subscription update --name es3 \\
1099	            -g rg1 --system-topic-name systemtopic1 \\
1100	            --subject-ends-with .png \\
1101	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
1102	            --included-event-types Microsoft.Storage.BlobCreated Microsoft.Storage.BlobDeleted
1103	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Azure Event Grid system topic, to include a deadletter destination.
1104	    text: |
1105	        az eventgrid system-topic event-subscription update --name es2 \\
1106	            -g rg1 --system-topic-name systemtopic1 \\
1107	            --deadletter-endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/TestRG/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/sa1/blobServices/default/containers/blobcontainer1
1108	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Azure Event Grid system topic, using advanced filters.
1109	    text: |
1110	        az eventgrid system-topic event-subscription update --name es3 \\
1111	            -g rg1 --system-topic-name systemtopic1 \\
1112	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
1113	            --advanced-filter data.blobType StringIn BlockBlob
1114	            --advanced-filter data.url StringBeginsWith https://myaccount.blob.core.windows.net
1115	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Event Grid system topic with Storage Queue as destination with ttl of 5 mins
1116	    text: |
1117	        az eventgrid system-topic event-subscription update -n es1 \\
1118	            -g rg1 --system-topic-name systemtopic1 \\
1119	            --storage-queue-msg-ttl 300
1120	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Event Grid system topic with advanced filtering on arrays enabled
1121	    text: |
1122	        az eventgrid system-topic event-subscription update -n es1 \\
1123	            -g rg1 --system-topic-name systemtopic1 \\
1124	            --enable-advanced-filtering-on-arrays true
