1397	    short-summary: The type of the destination endpoint with resource identity.
1398	  - name: --delivery-attribute-mapping
1399	    short-summary: Add delivery attribute mapping to send additional information via HTTP headers when delivering events. This attribute is valid for all destination types except StorageQueue. Multiple attributes can be specified by using more than one `--delivery-attribute-mapping` argument.
1400	    long-summary: |
1401	        Usage:                        --delivery-attribute-mapping attribute-name attribute-type attribute-value [attribute-is-secret]
1402	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue
1403	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue false
1404	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue true
1405	        Dynamic Attribute Mapping:    --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue
1406	        Both Static and Dynamic:      --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue --delivery-attribute-mapping somename2 static somevalue
1407	examples:
1408	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid topic, using default filters.
1409	    text: |
1410	        az eventgrid event-subscription create --name es1 \\
1411	            --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/Microsoft.EventGrid/topics/topic1 \\
1412	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
1413	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Azure subscription, using default filters.
1414	    text: |
1415	        az eventgrid event-subscription create --name es2 \\
1416	            --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID} \\
1417	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
1418	  - name: Create a new event subscription for a resource group, using default filters.
1419	    text: |
1420	        az eventgrid event-subscription create --name es3 \\
1421	            --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG} \\
1422	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
1423	  - name: Create a new event subscription for a storage account, using default filters.
1424	    text: |
1425	        az eventgrid event-subscription create --name es3 \\
1426	            --source-resource-id "/subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageaccounts/s1"  \\
1427	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
1428	  - name: Create a new event subscription for a storage account, using advanced filters.
1429	    text: |
1430	        az eventgrid event-subscription create  --name es3 \\
1431	            --source-resource-id "/subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageaccounts/s1" \\

1433	            --advanced-filter data.blobType StringIn BlockBlob
1434	            --advanced-filter data.url StringBeginsWith https://myaccount.blob.core.windows.net
1435	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Azure subscription, with a filter specifying a subject prefix.
1436	    text: |
1437	        az eventgrid event-subscription create --name es4 \\
1438	            --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID} \\
1439	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code \\

1441	  - name: Create a new event subscription for a resource group, with a filter specifying a subject suffix.
1442	    text: |
1443	        az eventgrid event-subscription create --name es5 \\
1444	            --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG} \\
1445	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code \\
1446	            --subject-ends-with mysubject_suffix
1447	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Azure subscription, using default filters, and an EventHub as a destination.

1457	            --endpoint-type storagequeue \\
1458	            --endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/TestRG/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/sa1/queueservices/default/queues/q1
1459	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Azure subscription, using default filters, and an Azure ServiceBusQueue as a destination.
1460	    text: |
1461	        az eventgrid event-subscription create --name es2 \\

1463	            --endpoint-type servicebusqueue \\
1464	            --endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/TestRG/providers/Microsoft.ServiceBus/namespaces/ns1/queues/queue1
1465	  - name: Create a new event subscription for an Event Grid domain, using default filters, and CloudEvent V 1.0 as the delivery schema.
1466	    text: |
1467	      az eventgrid event-subscription create --name es2 \\
1468	          --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/Microsoft.EventGrid/domains/d1 \\

1471	  - name: Create a new event subscription for a storage account, with a deadletter destination and custom retry policy of maximum 10 delivery attempts and an Event TTL of 2 hours (whichever happens earlier).

1680	type: command
1681	short-summary: Update an event subscription.
1682	parameters:
1683	  - name: --source-resource-id
1684	    short-summary: Fully qualified identifier of the Azure resource whose event subscription needs to be updated.
1685	    long-summary: |
1686	        Usage:                      --source-resource-id Azure-Resource-ID
1687	        For Azure subscription:     --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}
1688	        For resource group:         --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/rg1
1689	        For EventGrid topic:        --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/rg1/providers/Microsoft.EventGrid/topics/t1
1690	        For storage account:        --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/rg1/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageaccounts/sa1
1691	        For EventGrid domain:       --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/rg1/providers/Microsoft.EventGrid/domains/d1
1692	        For EventGrid domain topic: --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/rg1/providers/Microsoft.EventGrid/domains/d1/topics/t1
1693	  - name: --endpoint-type
1694	    short-summary: The type of the destination endpoint.
1695	  - name: --delivery-identity-endpoint-type
1696	    short-summary: The type of the destination endpoint with resource identity.
1697	  - name: --advanced-filter
1698	    short-summary: An advanced filter enables filtering of events based on a specific event property.
1699	    long-summary: |
1700	        Usage:                     --advanced-filter KEY[.INNERKEY] FILTEROPERATOR VALUE [VALUE ...]
1701	        StringIn:                  --advanced-filter data.Color StringIn Blue Red Orange Yellow
1702	        StringNotIn:               --advanced-filter data.Color StringNotIn Blue Red Orange Yellow
1703	        StringContains:            --advanced-filter subject StringContains Blue Red
1704	        StringNotContains:         --advanced-filter subject StringNotContains Blue Red
1705	        StringBeginsWith:          --advanced-filter subject StringBeginsWith Blue Red
1706	        StringNotBeginsWith:       --advanced-filter subject StringNotBeginsWith Blue Red
1707	        StringEndsWith:            --advanced-filter subject StringEndsWith img png jpg
1708	        StringNotEndsWith:         --advanced-filter subject StringNotEndsWith img png jpg
1709	        NumberIn:                  --advanced-filter data.property1 NumberIn 5 10 20
1710	        NumberInRange              --advanced-filter data.property1 NumberInRange 5,10 20,30 40,50
1711	        NumberNotIn:               --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberNotIn 100 200 300
1712	        NumberNotInRange:          --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberNotInRange 100,110 200,210 300,310
1713	        NumberLessThan:            --advanced-filter data.property3 NumberLessThan 100
1714	        NumberLessThanOrEquals:    --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberLessThanOrEquals 100
1715	        NumberGreaterThan:         --advanced-filter data.property3 NumberGreaterThan 100
1716	        NumberGreaterThanOrEquals: --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberGreaterThanOrEquals 100
1717	        BoolEquals:                --advanced-filter data.property3 BoolEquals true
1718	        IsNullOrUndefined:         --advanced-filter data.property3 IsNullOrUndefined
1719	        IsNotNull:                 --advanced-filter data.property3 IsNotNull
1720	        Multiple advanced filters can be specified by using more than one `--advanced-filter` argument.
1721	  - name: --delivery-attribute-mapping
1722	    short-summary: Add delivery attribute mapping to send additional information via HTTP headers when delivering events. This attribute is valid for all destination types except StorageQueue. Multiple attributes can be specified by using more than one `--delivery-attribute-mapping` argument.
1723	    long-summary: |
1724	        Usage:                        --delivery-attribute-mapping attribute-name attribute-type attribute-value [attribute-is-secret]
1725	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue
1726	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue false
1727	        Static Attribute Mapping:     --delivery-attribute-mapping somename static somevalue true
1728	        Dynamic Attribute Mapping:    --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue
1729	        Both Static and Dynamic:      --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue --delivery-attribute-mapping somename2 static somevalue
1730	examples:
1731	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Event Grid topic to specify a new endpoint.
1732	    text: |
1733	        az eventgrid event-subscription update --name es1 \\
1734	            --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/Microsoft.EventGrid/topics/topic1 \\
1735	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
1736	  - name: Update an event subscription for an Azure subscription to specify a new subject-ends-with filter.
1737	    text: |
1738	        az eventgrid event-subscription update --name es2 \\
1739	            --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID} \\
1740	            --subject-ends-with .jpg
1741	  - name: Update an event subscription for a resource group to specify a new endpoint and a new subject-ends-with filter.
1742	    text: |
1743	        az eventgrid event-subscription update --name es3 \\
1744	            --source-resource-id /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG} \\
1745	            --subject-ends-with .png \\
1746	            --endpoint https://contoso.azurewebsites.net/api/f1?code=code
1747	  - name: Update an event subscription for a storage account to specify a new list of included event types.
1748	    text: |
1749	        az eventgrid event-subscription update --name es3 \\
1750	            --source-resource-id "/subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/microsoft.storage/storageaccounts/kalsegblob" \\
1751	            --included-event-types Microsoft.Storage.BlobCreated Microsoft.Storage.BlobDeleted
1752	  - name: Update an event subscription for a storage account, to include a deadletter destination.
1753	    text: |
1754	        az eventgrid event-subscription update --name es2 \\
1755	            --source-resource-id "/subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageaccounts/kalsegblob" \\
1756	            --deadletter-endpoint /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/TestRG/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/sa1/blobServices/default/containers/blobcontainer1
1757	  - name: Update an event subscription for a storage account, using advanced filters.
1758	    text: |
1759	        az eventgrid event-subscription update --name es3 \\
1760	            --source-resource-id "/subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{RG}/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageaccounts/s1" \\

1768	            --storage-queue-msg-ttl 300

2025	        Usage:                     --advanced-filter KEY[.INNERKEY] FILTEROPERATOR VALUE [VALUE ...]
2026	        StringIn:                  --advanced-filter data.Color StringIn Blue Red Orange Yellow
2027	        StringNotIn:               --advanced-filter data.Color StringNotIn Blue Red Orange Yellow
2028	        StringContains:            --advanced-filter subject StringContains Blue Red
2029	        StringNotContains:         --advanced-filter subject StringNotContains Blue Red
2030	        StringBeginsWith:          --advanced-filter subject StringBeginsWith Blue Red
2031	        StringNotBeginsWith:       --advanced-filter subject StringNotBeginsWith Blue Red
2032	        StringEndsWith:            --advanced-filter subject StringEndsWith img png jpg
2033	        StringNotEndsWith:         --advanced-filter subject StringNotEndsWith img png jpg

2036	        NumberNotIn:               --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberNotIn 100 200 300
2037	        NumberNotInRange:          --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberNotInRange 100,110 200,210 300,310

2039	        NumberLessThanOrEquals:    --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberLessThanOrEquals 100
2040	        NumberGreaterThan:         --advanced-filter data.property3 NumberGreaterThan 100
2041	        NumberGreaterThanOrEquals: --advanced-filter data.property2 NumberGreaterThanOrEquals 100

2043	        IsNullOrUndefined:         --advanced-filter data.property3 IsNullOrUndefined
2044	        IsNotNull:                 --advanced-filter data.property3 IsNotNull
2045	        Multiple advanced filters can be specified by using more than one `--advanced-filter` argument.
2046	  - name: --delivery-attribute-mapping -d
2047	    short-summary: Add delivery attribute mapping to send additional information via HTTP headers when delivering events. This attribute is valid for all destination types except StorageQueue. Multiple attributes can be specified by using more than one `--delivery-attribute-mapping` argument.
2048	    long-summary: |
2049	        Usage:                        --delivery-attribute-mapping attribute-name attribute-type attribute-value [attribute-is-secret]

2053	        Dynamic Attribute Mapping:    --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue
2054	        Both Static and Dynamic:      --delivery-attribute-mapping somename dynamic somevalue --delivery-attribute-mapping somename2 static somevalue

33	  - name: Add extension to system directory

35	  - name: Add a specific version of extension
36	    text: az extension add --name anextension --version 1.0.0

57	helps['hdinsight create'] = """
58	type: command
59	short-summary: Create a new cluster.
60	examples:
61	  - name: Create a cluster with an existing storage account.
62	    text: |-
63	        az hdinsight create -t spark -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
64	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" \\
65	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount
66	  - name: Create a cluster with minimal tls version.
67	    text: |-
68	        az hdinsight create -t spark -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
69	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" \\
70	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount --minimal-tls-version 1.2
71	  - name: Create a cluster which enables encryption in transit.
72	    text: |-
73	        az hdinsight create -t spark -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
74	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" \\
75	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount --encryption-in-transit true
76	  - name: Create a cluster with encryption at host.
77	    text: |-
78	        az hdinsight create -t spark -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
79	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" \\
80	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount --encryption-at-host true
81	  - name: Create a cluster with the Enterprise Security Package (ESP).
82	    text: |-
83	        az hdinsight create --esp -t spark -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
84	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" \\
85	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
86	        --subnet "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/MyRG/providers/Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks/MyVnet/subnets/subnet1" \\
87	        --domain "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/MyRG/providers/Microsoft.AAD/domainServices/MyDomain.onmicrosoft.com" \\
88	        --assign-identity "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourcegroups/MyMsiRG/providers/Microsoft.ManagedIdentity/userAssignedIdentities/MyMSI" \\
89	        --cluster-admin-account MyAdminAccount@MyDomain.onmicrosoft.com \\
90	        --cluster-users-group-dns MyGroup
91	  - name: Create a cluster with the Enterprise Security Package (ESP) and enable HDInsight ID Broker.
92	    text: |-
93	        az hdinsight create --esp --idbroker -t spark -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
94	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" \\
95	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
96	        --subnet "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/MyRG/providers/Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks/MyVnet/subnets/subnet1" \\
97	        --domain "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/MyRG/providers/Microsoft.AAD/domainServices/MyDomain.onmicrosoft.com" \\
98	        --assign-identity "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourcegroups/MyMsiRG/providers/Microsoft.ManagedIdentity/userAssignedIdentities/MyMSI" \\
99	        --cluster-admin-account MyAdminAccount@MyDomain.onmicrosoft.com \\
100	        --cluster-users-group-dns MyGroup
101	  - name: Create a Kafka cluster with disk encryption. See https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/hdinsight/kafka/apache-kafka-byok.
102	    text: |-
103	        az hdinsight create -t kafka -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
104	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" --workernode-data-disks-per-node 2 \\
105	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
106	        --encryption-key-name kafkaClusterKey \\
107	        --encryption-key-version 00000000000000000000000000000000 \\
108	        --encryption-vault-uri https://MyKeyVault.vault.azure.net \\
109	        --assign-identity MyMSI
110	  - name: Create a kafka cluster with kafka rest proxy.
111	    text: |-
112	        az hdinsight create -t kafka -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
113	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" --workernode-data-disks-per-node 2 \\
114	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
115	        --kafka-management-node-size "Standard_D4_v2" \\
116	        --kafka-client-group-id MySecurityGroupId \\
117	        --kafka-client-group-name MySecurityGroupName
118	        --component-version kafka=2.1
119	  - name: Create a cluster with Azure Data Lake Storage Gen2
120	    text: |-
121	        az hdinsight create -t spark -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
122	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" \\
123	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
124	        --storage-account-managed-identity MyMSI
125	  - name: Create a cluster with configuration from JSON string.
126	    text: |-
127	        az hdinsight create -t spark -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
128	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" \\
129	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
130	        --cluster-configuration {'gateway':{'restAuthCredential.username':'admin'}}
131	  - name: Create a cluster with configuration from a local file.
132	    text: |-
133	        az hdinsight create -t spark -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
134	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" \\
135	        --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
136	        --cluster-configuration @config.json
137	  - name: Create a cluster which Load-based Autoscale.
138	    text: |-
139	        az hdinsight create -t spark --version 3.6 -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
140	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
141	        --autoscale-type Load --autoscale-min-workernode-count 3 --autoscale-max-workernode-count 5
142	  - name: Create a cluster which Schedule-based Autoscale.
143	    text: |-
144	        az hdinsight create -t spark --version 3.6 -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
145	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
146	        --autoscale-type Schedule --timezone "Pacific Standard Time" --days Monday \\
147	        --time 09:00 --autoscale-workernode-count 5
148	  - name: Create a cluster with Relay Outbound and Private Link feature.
149	    text: |-
150	        az hdinsight create -t spark --version 3.6 -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
151	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
152	        --subnet "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/rg/providers/Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks/fakevnet/subnets/default" \\
153	        --resource-provider-connection Outbound --enable-private-link
154	  - name: Create a cluster with Compute Isolation feature.
155	    text: |-
156	        az hdinsight create -t spark --version 3.6 -g MyResourceGroup -n MyCluster \\
157	        -p "HttpPassword1234!" --storage-account MyStorageAccount \\
158	        --enable-compute-isolation --workernode-size "Standard_E8S_V3" --headnode-size "Standard_E8S_V3"
159	"""

86	helps['monitor autoscale create'] = """
87	type: command
88	short-summary: Create new autoscale settings.
89	long-summary: >
90	    For more information on autoscaling, visit: https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/monitoring-and-diagnostics/monitoring-understanding-autoscale-settings
91	parameters:
92	  - name: --action -a
93	    short-summary: Add an action to fire when a scaling event occurs.
94	    long-summary: |
95	        Usage:   --action TYPE KEY [ARG ...]
96	        Email:   --action email bob@contoso.com ann@contoso.com
97	        Webhook: --action webhook https://www.contoso.com/alert apiKey=value
98	        Webhook: --action webhook https://www.contoso.com/alert?apiKey=value
99	        Multiple actions can be specified by using more than one `--action` argument.
100	examples:
101	  - name: Create autoscale settings to scale between 2 and 5 instances (3 as default). Email the administrator when scaling occurs.
102	    text: |
103	        az monitor autoscale create -g {myrg} --resource {resource-id} --min-count 2 --max-count 5 \\
104	          --count 3 --email-administrator
105	
106	        az monitor autoscale rule create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {resource-name} --scale out 1 \\
107	          --condition "Percentage CPU > 75 avg 5m"
108	
109	        az monitor autoscale rule create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {resource-name} --scale in 1 \\
110	          --condition "Percentage CPU < 25 avg 5m"
111	  - name: Create autoscale settings for exactly 4 instances.
112	    text: >
113	        az monitor autoscale create -g {myrg} --resource {resource-id} --count 4
114	  - name: Create new autoscale settings. (autogenerated)
115	    text: |
116	        az monitor autoscale create --count 3 --max-count 5 --min-count 2 --name MyAutoscaleSettings --resource myScaleSet --resource-group MyResourceGroup --resource-type Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachineScaleSets
117	    crafted: true
118	"""

126	
127	helps['monitor autoscale profile create'] = """
128	type: command
129	short-summary: Create a fixed or recurring autoscale profile.
130	long-summary: >
131	    For more information on autoscaling, visit: https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/monitoring-and-diagnostics/monitoring-understanding-autoscale-settings
132	parameters:
133	  - name: --timezone
134	    short-summary: Timezone name.
135	    populator-commands:
136	      - az monitor autoscale profile list-timezones
137	  - name: --recurrence -r
138	    short-summary: When the profile recurs. If omitted, a fixed (non-recurring) profile is created.
139	    long-summary: |
140	        Usage:     --recurrence {week} [ARG ARG ...]
141	        Weekly:    --recurrence week Sat Sun
142	  - name: --start
143	    short-summary: When the autoscale profile begins. Format depends on the type of profile.
144	    long-summary: |
145	        Fixed:  --start yyyy-mm-dd [hh:mm:ss]
146	        Weekly: [--start hh:mm]
147	  - name: --end
148	    short-summary: When the autoscale profile ends. Format depends on the type of profile.
149	    long-summary: |
150	        Fixed:  --end yyyy-mm-dd [hh:mm:ss]
151	        Weekly: [--end hh:mm]
152	examples:
153	  - name: Create a fixed date profile, inheriting the default scaling rules but changing the capacity.
154	    text: |
155	        az monitor autoscale create -g {myrg} --resource {resource-id} --min-count 2 --count 3 \\
156	          --max-count 5
157	
158	        az monitor autoscale rule create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {name} --scale out 1 \\
159	          --condition "Percentage CPU > 75 avg 5m"
160	
161	        az monitor autoscale rule create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {name} --scale in 1 \\
162	          --condition "Percentage CPU < 25 avg 5m"
163	
164	        az monitor autoscale profile create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {name} -n Christmas \\
165	          --copy-rules default --min-count 3 --count 6 --max-count 10 --start 2018-12-24 \\
166	          --end 2018-12-26 --timezone "Pacific Standard Time"
167	  - name: Create a recurring weekend profile, inheriting the default scaling rules but changing the capacity.
168	    text: |
169	        az monitor autoscale create -g {myrg} --resource {resource-id} --min-count 2 --count 3 \\
170	          --max-count 5
171	
172	        az monitor autoscale rule create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {name} --scale out 1 \\
173	          --condition "Percentage CPU > 75 avg 5m"
174	
175	        az monitor autoscale rule create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {name} --scale in 1 \\
176	          --condition "Percentage CPU < 25 avg 5m"
177	
178	        az monitor autoscale profile create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {name} -n weeekend \\
179	          --copy-rules default --min-count 1 --count 2 --max-count 2 \\
180	          --recurrence week sat sun --timezone "Pacific Standard Time"
181	  - name: Create a fixed or recurring autoscale profile. (autogenerated)
182	    text: |
183	        az monitor autoscale profile create --autoscale-name MyAutoscale --copy-rules default --count 2 --end 2018-12-26 --max-count 10 --min-count 1 --name Christmas --recurrence week sat sun --resource-group MyResourceGroup --start 2018-12-24 --timezone "Pacific Standard Time"
184	    crafted: true
185	  - name: Create a fixed or recurring autoscale profile. (autogenerated)
186	    text: |
187	        az monitor autoscale profile create --autoscale-name MyAutoscale --count 2 --max-count 10 --min-count 1 --name Christmas --recurrence week sat sun --resource-group MyResourceGroup --start 2018-12-24 --subscription MySubscription --timezone "Pacific Standard Time"
188	    crafted: true
189	"""

234	type: command
235	short-summary: Add a new autoscale rule.
236	long-summary: >
237	    For more information on autoscaling, visit: https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/monitoring-and-diagnostics/monitoring-understanding-autoscale-settings
238	parameters:
239	  - name: --condition
240	    short-summary: The condition which triggers the scaling action.
241	    long-summary: >
242	        Usage:  --condition ["NAMESPACE"] METRIC {==,!=,>,>=,<,<=} THRESHOLD
243	                            {avg,min,max,total,count} PERIOD
244	                            [where DIMENSION {==,!=} VALUE [or VALUE ...]
245	                            [and   DIMENSION {==,!=} VALUE [or VALUE ...] ...]]
246	
247	        Dimensions can be queried by adding the 'where' keyword and multiple dimensions can be queried by combining them with the 'and' keyword.
248	        Values for METRIC and appropriate THRESHOLD values can be obtained from the `az monitor metric` command.
249	        Format of PERIOD is "##h##m##s".
250	  - name: --scale
251	    short-summary: The direction and amount to scale.
252	    long-summary: |
253	        Usage:          --scale {to,in,out} VAL[%]
254	        Fixed Count:    --scale to 5
255	        In by Count:    --scale in 2
256	        Out by Percent: --scale out 10%
257	  - name: --timegrain
258	    short-summary: >
259	        The way metrics are polled across instances.
260	    long-summary: >
261	        The form of the timegrain is {avg,min,max,sum} VALUE. Values can be obtained from the `az monitor metric` command.
262	        Format of VALUE is "##h##m##s".
263	examples:
264	  - name: Scale to 5 instances when the CPU Percentage across instances is greater than 75 averaged over 10 minutes.
265	    text: |
266	        az monitor autoscale rule create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {myvmss} \\
267	          --scale to 5 --condition "Percentage CPU > 75 avg 10m"
268	  - name: Scale up 2 instances when the CPU Percentage across instances is greater than 75 averaged over 5 minutes.
269	    text: |
270	        az monitor autoscale rule create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {myvmss} \\
271	          --scale out 2 --condition "Percentage CPU > 75 avg 5m"
272	  - name: Scale down 50% when the CPU Percentage across instances is less than 25 averaged over 15 minutes.
273	    text: |
274	        az monitor autoscale rule create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name {myvmss} \\
275	          --scale in 50% --condition "Percentage CPU < 25 avg 15m"
276	  - name: Create autoscale settings via a guest vm metric enabled from diagnostic extensions.
277	          You can use counterSpecifier field retrieved from 'az vmss diagnostics get-default-config' in the `--condition`.
278	    text: |
279	        az monitor autoscale rule create -g {myrg} --autoscale-name test --scale out 1 --condition "/builtin/memory/percentavailablememory > 80 total 5m"
280	
281	"""

527	type: command
528	short-summary: List the metric values for a resource.
529	parameters:
530	  - name: --aggregation
531	    short-summary: The list of aggregation types (space-separated) to retrieve.
532	    populator-commands:
533	      - az monitor metrics list-definitions
534	  - name: --interval
535	    short-summary: >
536	        The interval over which to aggregate metrics, in ##h##m format.
537	  - name: --filter
538	    short-summary: A string used to reduce the set of metric data returned. eg. "BlobType eq '*'"
539	    long-summary: 'For a full list of filters, see the filter string reference at https://learn.microsoft.com/rest/api/monitor/metrics/list'
540	  - name: --metadata
541	    short-summary: Returns the metadata values instead of metric data
542	  - name: --dimension
543	    short-summary: The list of dimensions (space-separated) the metrics are queried into.
544	    populator-commands:
545	      - az monitor metrics list-definitions
546	  - name: --namespace
547	    short-summary: Namespace to query metric definitions for.
548	    populator-commands:
549	      - az monitor metrics list-namespaces
550	  - name: --offset
551	    short-summary: >
552	        Time offset of the query range, in ##d##h format.
553	    long-summary: >
554	        Can be used with either --start-time or --end-time. If used with --start-time, then
555	        the end time will be calculated by adding the offset. If used with --end-time (default), then
556	        the start time will be calculated by subtracting the offset. If --start-time and --end-time are
557	        provided, then --offset will be ignored.
558	  - name: --metrics
559	    short-summary: >
560	        Space-separated list of metric names to retrieve.
561	    populator-commands:
562	      - az monitor metrics list-definitions
563	
564	examples:
565	  - name: List a VM's CPU usage for the past hour
566	    text: >
567	        az monitor metrics list --resource {ResourceName} --metric "Percentage CPU"
568	  - name: List success E2E latency of a storage account and split the data series based on API name
569	    text: >
570	        az monitor metrics list --resource {ResourceName} --metric SuccessE2ELatency \\
571	                                --dimension ApiName
572	  - name: List success E2E latency of a storage account and split the data series based on both API name and geo type
573	    text: >
574	        az monitor metrics list --resource {ResourceName} --metric SuccessE2ELatency \\
575	                                --dimension ApiName GeoType
576	  - name: List success E2E latency of a storage account and split the data series based on both API name and geo type using "--filter" parameter
577	    text: >
578	        az monitor metrics list --resource {ResourceName} --metric SuccessE2ELatency \\
579	                                --filter "ApiName eq '*' and GeoType eq '*'"
580	  - name: List success E2E latency of a storage account and split the data series based on both API name and geo type. Limits the api name to 'DeleteContainer'
581	    text: >
582	        az monitor metrics list --resource {ResourceName} --metric SuccessE2ELatency \\
583	                                --filter "ApiName eq 'DeleteContainer' and GeoType eq '*'"
584	  - name: List transactions of a storage account per day since 2017-01-01
585	    text: >
586	        az monitor metrics list --resource {ResourceName} --metric Transactions \\
587	                                --start-time 2017-01-01T00:00:00Z \\
588	                                --interval PT24H
589	  - name: List the metadata values for a storage account under transaction metric's api name dimension since 2017
590	    text: >
591	        az monitor metrics list --resource {ResourceName} --metric Transactions \\
592	                                --filter "ApiName eq '*'" \\
593	                                --start-time 2017-01-01T00:00:00Z

42	helps['mysql flexible-server create'] = """
43	type: command
44	short-summary: Create a MySQL flexible server.
45	long-summary: >
46	    Create a MySQL flexible server with custom or default configuration. For more information for network configuration, see
47	
48	    - Configure public access
49	
50	    https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/mysql/flexible-server/how-to-manage-firewall-cli
51	
52	    - Configure private access
53	
54	    https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/mysql/flexible-server/how-to-manage-virtual-network-cli
55	
56	examples:
57	  - name: >
58	      Create a MySQL flexible server with custom parameters
59	    text: >
60	        az mysql flexible-server create --location northeurope --resource-group testGroup \\
61	          --name testserver --admin-user username --admin-password password \\
62	          --sku-name Standard_B1ms --tier Burstable --public-access 0.0.0.0 --storage-size 32 \\
63	          --tags "key=value" --version 5.7 --high-availability ZoneRedundant --zone 1 \\
64	          --standby-zone 3 --storage-auto-grow Enabled --iops 500
65	  - name: >
66	      Create a MySQL flexible server with default parameters and public access enabled by default. \
67	      Resource group, server name, username, password, and default database will be created by CLI
68	    text: >
69	        az mysql flexible-server create
70	  - name: >
71	      Create a MySQL flexible server with public access and add the range of IP address to have access to this server.
72	      The --public-access parameter can be 'All', 'None', <startIpAddress>, or <startIpAddress>-<endIpAddress>
73	    text: >
74	      az mysql flexible-server create --resource-group testGroup --name testserver --public-access 125.23.54.31-125.23.54.35
75	  - name: >
76	      Create a MySQL flexible server with private access. If provided virtual network and subnet do not exists, virtual network and subnet with the specified address prefixes will be created.
77	    text: >
78	      az mysql flexible-server create --resource-group testGroup --name testserver --vnet myVnet --subnet mySubnet --address-prefixes 10.0.0.0/16 --subnet-prefixes 10.0.0.0/24
79	  - name: >
80	      Create a MySQL flexible server using a new subnet resource ID and new private DNS zone resource ID. The subnet and DNS zone can be created in different subscription or resource group.
81	    text: |
82	      az mysql flexible-server create \\
83	        --resource-group testGroup --name testserver \\
84	        --subnet /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{ResourceGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks/{VNetName}/subnets/{SubnetName} \\
85	        --private-dns-zone /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{resourceGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Network/privateDnsZones/testMySQLFlexibleDnsZone.private.mysql.database.azure.com \\
86	        --address-prefixes 172.0.0.0/16 --subnet-prefixes 172.0.0.0/24
87	  - name: >
88	      Create a MySQL flexible server using existing network resources in the same resource group.
89	      The provided subnet should not have any other resource deployed in it and this subnet will be delegated to Microsoft.DBforMySQL/flexibleServers, if not already delegated.
90	      The private DNS zone will be linked to the virtual network if not already linked.
91	    text: >
92	      # create vnet
93	
94	      az network vnet create --resource-group testGroup --name testVnet --location testLocation --address-prefixes 172.0.0.0/16
95	
96	
97	      # create subnet
98	
99	      az network vnet subnet create --resource-group testGroup --vnet-name testVnet --address-prefixes 172.0.0.0/24 --name testSubnet
100	
101	
102	      # create private dns zone
103	
104	      az network private-dns zone create -g testGroup -n testDNS.private.mysql.database.azure.com
105	
106	
107	      az mysql flexible-server create --resource-group testGroup \\
108	        --name testserver --location testLocation \\
109	        --subnet /subscriptions/{SubId}/resourceGroups/{testGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks/tesetVnet/subnets/testSubnet \\
110	        --private-dns-zone /subscriptions/{SubId}/resourceGroups/{testGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Network/privateDnsZones/testDNS.mysql.database.azure.com\\
111	
112	
113	      az mysql flexible-server create --resource-group testGroup --name testserver \\
114	        --vnet testVnet --subnet testSubnet --location testLocation \\
115	        --private-dns-zone /subscriptions/{SubId}/resourceGroups/{testGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Network/privateDnsZones/testDNS.mysql.database.azure.com
116	  - name: >
117	      Create a MySQL flexible server using existing network resources in the different resource group / subscription.
118	    text: >
119	      az mysql flexible-server create --resource-group testGroup \\
120	         --name testserver --location testLocation \\
121	        --subnet /subscriptions/{SubId2}/resourceGroups/{testGroup2}/providers/Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks/tesetVnet/subnets/testSubnet \\
122	        --private-dns-zone /subscriptions/{SubId2}/resourceGroups/{testGroup2}/providers/Microsoft.Network/privateDnsZones/testDNS.mysql.database.azure.com
123	  - name: >
124	      Create a MySQL flexible server with data encryption.
125	    text: >
126	      # create keyvault
127	
128	      az keyvault create -g testGroup -n testVault --location testLocation \\
129	        --enable-purge-protection true
130	
131	
132	      # create key in keyvault and save its key identifier
133	
134	      keyIdentifier=$(az keyvault key create --name testKey -p software \\
135	        --vault-name testVault --query key.kid -o tsv)
136	
137	
138	      # create identity and save its principalId
139	
140	      identityPrincipalId=$(az identity create -g testGroup --name testIdentity \\
141	        --location testLocation --query principalId -o tsv)
142	
143	
144	      # add testIdentity as an access policy with key permissions 'Wrap Key', 'Unwrap Key', 'Get' and 'List' inside testVault
145	
146	      az keyvault set-policy -g testGroup -n testVault --object-id $identityPrincipalId \\
147	        --key-permissions wrapKey unwrapKey get list
148	
149	
150	      # create flexible server with data encryption enabled
151	
152	      az mysql flexible-server create -g testGroup -n testServer --location testLocation \\
153	        --key $keyIdentifier --identity testIdentity
154	  - name: >
155	      Create a MySQL flexible server with geo redundant backup and data encryption.
156	    text: >
157	      # create keyvault
158	
159	      az keyvault create -g testGroup -n testVault --location testLocation \\
160	        --enable-purge-protection true
161	
162	
163	      # create key in keyvault and save its key identifier
164	
165	      keyIdentifier=$(az keyvault key create --name testKey -p software \\
166	        --vault-name testVault --query key.kid -o tsv)
167	
168	
169	      # create identity and save its principalId
170	
171	      identityPrincipalId=$(az identity create -g testGroup --name testIdentity \\
172	        --location testLocation --query principalId -o tsv)
173	
174	
175	      # add testIdentity as an access policy with key permissions 'Wrap Key', 'Unwrap Key', 'Get' and 'List' inside testVault
176	
177	      az keyvault set-policy -g testGroup -n testVault --object-id $identityPrincipalId \\
178	        --key-permissions wrapKey unwrapKey get list
179	
180	
181	      # create backup keyvault
182	
183	      az keyvault create -g testGroup -n testBackupVault --location testBackupLocation \\
184	        --enable-purge-protection true
185	
186	
187	      # create backup key in backup keyvault and save its key identifier
188	
189	      backupKeyIdentifier=$(az keyvault key create --name testBackupKey -p software \\
190	        --vault-name testBackupVault --query key.kid -o tsv)
191	
192	
193	      # create backup identity and save its principalId
194	
195	      backupIdentityPrincipalId=$(az identity create -g testGroup --name testBackupIdentity \\
196	        --location testBackupLocation --query principalId -o tsv)
197	
198	
199	      # add testBackupIdentity as an access policy with key permissions 'Wrap Key', 'Unwrap Key', 'Get' and 'List' inside testBackupVault
200	
201	      az keyvault set-policy -g testGroup -n testBackupVault \\
202	        --object-id $backupIdentityPrincipalId --key-permissions wrapKey unwrapKey get list
203	
204	
205	      # create flexible server with geo redundant backup and data encryption enabled
206	
207	      az mysql flexible-server create -g testGroup -n testServer --location testLocation \\
208	        --geo-redundant-backup Enabled \\
209	        --key $keyIdentifier --identity testIdentity \\
210	        --backup-key $backupKeyIdentifier --backup-identity testBackupIdentity
211	"""

218	helps['mysql flexible-server import create'] = """
219	type: command
220	short-summary: Create a new import workflow for flexible server.
221	long-summary: >
222	    This command is used for following two purposes:
223	
224	    To Migrate an external MySQL server to Azure MySQL Flexible server whose backup is stored on an Azure Blob Container.
225	
226	    To Migrate a Azure MySQL single server to Azure MySQL Flexible server. For more information for network configuration, see
227	
228	    - Migrate Azure Database for MySQL - Single Server to Flexible Server using Azure Database for MySQL Import CLI
229	
230	    https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/mysql/migrate/migrate-single-flexible-mysql-import-cli
231	
232	    - Configure public access
233	
234	    https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/mysql/flexible-server/how-to-manage-firewall-cli
235	
236	    - Configure private access
237	
238	    https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/mysql/flexible-server/how-to-manage-virtual-network-cli
239	
240	examples:
241	  - name: >
242	      Trigger an Import from azure mysql single server.
243	    text: >
244	        az mysql flexible-server import create --data-source-type mysql_single \\
245	          --data-source test-single-server --resource-group test-rg \\
246	          --location northeurope --name testserver \\
247	          --sku-name Standard_B1ms --tier Burstable --public-access 0.0.0.0 \\
248	          --storage-size 32 --tags "key=value" --version 5.7 --high-availability ZoneRedundant \\
249	          --zone 1 --standby-zone 3 --storage-auto-grow Enabled --iops 500
250	  - name: >
251	      Trigger an Online Import from azure mysql single server.
252	    text: >
253	        az mysql flexible-server import create --data-source-type mysql_single \\
254	          --data-source test-single-server --mode "Online" --resource-group test-rg \\
255	          --location northeurope --name testserver \\
256	          --sku-name Standard_B1ms --tier Burstable --public-access 0.0.0.0 \\
257	          --storage-size 32 --tags "key=value" --version 5.7 --high-availability ZoneRedundant \\
258	          --zone 1 --standby-zone 3 --storage-auto-grow Enabled --iops 500
259	  - name: >
260	      Trigger a Import from source backup stored in azure blob container.
261	    text: >
262	        az mysql flexible-server import create --data-source-type "azure_blob" \\
263	          --data-source "https://teststorage.blob.windows.net/backupcontainer" \\
264	          --resource-group test-rg --name testserver --version 5.7 --location northeurope \\
265	          --admin-user "username" --admin-password "password" \\
266	          --sku-name Standard_D2ds_v4 --tier GeneralPurpose --public-access 0.0.0.0 \\
267	          --storage-size 32 --tags "key=value" --high-availability ZoneRedundant \\
268	          --zone 1 --standby-zone 3 --storage-auto-grow Enabled --iops 500
269	  - name: >
270	      Trigger import from source backup stored in azure blob container. (Backup files not present in container root. Instead present in backupdata/data/)
271	    text: >
272	        az mysql flexible-server import create --data-source-type "azure_blob" \\
273	          --data-source "https://teststorage.blob.windows.net/backupcontainer" \\
274	          --data-source-backup-dir "backupdata/data/" \\
275	          --resource-group test-rg --name testserver --version 5.7 --location northeurope \\
276	          --admin-user "username" --admin-password "password" \\
277	          --sku-name Standard_D2ds_v4 --tier GeneralPurpose --public-access 0.0.0.0 \\
278	          --storage-size 32 --tags "key=value" --high-availability ZoneRedundant \\
279	          --zone 1 --standby-zone 3 --storage-auto-grow Enabled --iops 500
280	  - name: >
281	      Trigger import from source backup stored in azure blob container.
282	      (Backup files present in container root and blob storage accessible through sas token with Read and List permissions. Please pass '--%' in the command with SAS token.)
283	    text: >
284	        az mysql flexible-server import create --data-source-type "azure_blob" \\
285	          --data-source "https://teststorage.blob.windows.net/backupcontainer" \\
286	          --data-source-sas-token "sp=r&st=2023-07-20T10:30:07Z..."  \\
287	          --resource-group test-rg --name testserver --version 5.7 --location northeurope \\
288	          --admin-user "username" --admin-password "password" \\
289	          --sku-name Standard_D2ds_v4 --tier GeneralPurpose --public-access 0.0.0.0 \\
290	          --storage-size 32 --tags "key=value" --high-availability ZoneRedundant \\
291	          --zone 1 --standby-zone 3 --storage-auto-grow Enabled --iops 500
292	"""

1567	      az network application-gateway waf-policy managed-rule rule-set update --policy-name MyPolicy -g MyResourceGroup --type OWASP --version 3.1 --group-name REQUEST-921-PROTOCOL-ATTACK --rule rule-id=921130 --rule rule-id=921160
1568	  - name: Update the OWASP protocol version from 3.1 to 3.0 which will clear the old rules
1569	    text: |
1570	      az network application-gateway waf-policy managed-rule rule-set update --policy-name MyPolicy -g MyResourceGroup --type OWASP --version 3.0
1571	"""

4463	            --destination-address-prefixes '*' --destination-port-ranges 80 8080 --access Deny \\
4464	            --protocol Tcp --description "Deny from specific IP address ranges on 80 and 8080."

4466	    text: |

4468	            --priority 400 --source-address-prefixes VirtualNetwork --destination-address-prefixes Storage \\
4469	            --destination-port-ranges '*' --direction Outbound --access Allow --protocol Tcp --description "Allow VirtualNetwork to Storage."
4470	  - name: Create a security rule using application security groups. https://aka.ms/applicationsecuritygroups
4471	    text: |

6146	long-summary: >
6147	    To check connectivity between two VMs in different regions, use the VM ids instead of the VM names for the source and destination resource arguments.
6148	    To register for this feature or see additional examples visit https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/network-watcher/network-watcher-connectivity-cli
6149	parameters:
6150	  - name: --source-resource
6151	    short-summary: Name or ID of the resource from which to originate traffic.
6152	    long-summary: Currently only Virtual Machines are supported.
6153	  - name: --source-port
6154	    short-summary: Port number from which to originate traffic.
6155	  - name: --dest-resource
6156	    short-summary: Name or ID of the resource to receive traffic.
6157	    long-summary: Currently only Virtual Machines are supported.
6158	  - name: --dest-port
6159	    short-summary: Port number on which to receive traffic.
6160	  - name: --dest-address
6161	    short-summary: The IP address or URI at which to receive traffic.
6162	examples:
6163	  - name: Check connectivity between two virtual machines in the same resource group over port 80.
6164	    text: az network watcher test-connectivity -g MyResourceGroup --source-resource MyVmName1 --dest-resource MyVmName2 --dest-port 80
6165	  - name: Check connectivity between two virtual machines in the same subscription in two different resource groups over port 80.
6166	    text: az network watcher test-connectivity --source-resource MyVmId1 --dest-resource MyVmId2 --dest-port 80
6167	"""

6188	examples:

6190	    text: |
6191	        az network watcher test-ip-flow -g MyResourceGroup --direction Outbound \\

11	type: command
12	short-summary: Log in to Azure.
13	long-summary: >-
14	    By default, this command logs in with a user account.
15	    Azure CLI uses Web Account Manager (WAM) on Windows, and browser-based login on Linux and macOS by default.
16	    If WAM or a web browser is not available, Azure CLI will fall back to device code login.
17	
18	
19	    [WARNING] Authentication with username and password in the command line is strongly discouraged.
20	    Use one of the recommended authentication methods based on your requirements.
21	    For more details, see https://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/?linkid=2276314
22	
23	
24	    [WARNING] `--password` no longer accepts a service principal certificate.
25	    Use `--certificate` to pass a service principal certificate.
26	
27	
28	    To log in with a service principal, specify --service-principal.
29	
30	
31	    To log in with a managed identity, specify --identity.
32	
33	
34	    For more details, see https://learn.microsoft.com/cli/azure/authenticate-azure-cli
35	examples:
36	    - name: Log in interactively.
37	      text: az login
38	    - name: Log in with username and password. This doesn't work with Microsoft accounts or accounts that have two-factor authentication enabled. Use -p=secret if the first character of the password is '-'.
39	      text: az login --username johndoe@contoso.com --password VerySecret
40	    - name: Log in with a service principal using client secret. Use --password=secret if the first character of the password is '-'.
41	      text: az login --service-principal --username APP_ID --password CLIENT_SECRET --tenant TENANT_ID
42	    - name: Log in with a service principal using certificate.
43	      text: az login --service-principal --username APP_ID --certificate /path/to/cert.pem --tenant TENANT_ID
44	    - name: Log in with a system-assigned managed identity.
45	      text: az login --identity
46	    - name: Log in with a user-assigned managed identity's client ID.
47	      text: az login --identity --client-id 00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000
48	    - name: Log in with a user-assigned managed identity's resource ID.
49	      text: az login --identity --resource-id /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/MyResourceGroup/providers/Microsoft.ManagedIdentity/userAssignedIdentities/MyIdentity

21	    Create a PostgreSQL flexible server with custom or default configuration. For more information for network configuration, see
22	
23	    - Configure public access
24

32	  - name: >
33	      Create a PostgreSQL flexible server with custom parameters
34	    text: >
35	        az postgres flexible-server create --location northeurope --resource-group testGroup \\
36	          --name testserver --admin-user username --admin-password password \\
37	          --sku-name Standard_D2s_v3 --tier GeneralPurpose --public-access 153.24.26.117 --storage-size 128 \\
38	          --tags "key=value" --version 17 --high-availability ZoneRedundant --zone 1 \\
39	          --standby-zone 3
40	  - name: >
41	      Create a PostgreSQL flexible server using Premium SSD v2 Disks.
42	    text: >
43	      # set storage type to "PremiumV2_LRS" and provide values for Storage size (in GiB), IOPS (operations/sec), and Throughput (MB/sec).
44	
45	      az postgres flexible-server create --location northeurope --resource-group testGroup \\
46	          --name testserver --admin-user username --admin-password password \\
47	          --sku-name Standard_B1ms --tier Burstable --storage-type PremiumV2_LRS --storage-size 128 --iops 3000 --throughput 125
48	  - name: >
49	      Create a PostgreSQL flexible server with default parameters and public access enabled by default. \
50	      Resource group, server name, username, password, and default database will be created by CLI
51	    text: >
52	        az postgres flexible-server create
53	  - name: >
54	      Create a PostgreSQL flexible server with public access and add the range of IP address to have access to this server.
55	      The --public-access parameter can be 'Disabled', 'Enabled', 'All', 'None', <startIpAddress>, or <startIpAddress>-<endIpAddress>
56	    text: >
57	      az postgres flexible-server create --resource-group testGroup --name testserver --public-access 125.23.54.31-125.23.54.35
58	  - name: >
59	      Create a PostgreSQL flexible server with private access. If provided virtual network and subnet do not exists, virtual network and subnet with the specified address prefixes will be created.
60	    text: >
61	      az postgres flexible-server create --resource-group testGroup --name testserver --vnet myVnet --subnet mySubnet --address-prefixes 10.0.0.0/16 --subnet-prefixes 10.0.0.0/24
62	  - name: >
63	      Create a PostgreSQL flexible server using a new subnet resource ID and new private DNS zone resource ID. The subnet and DNS zone can be created in different subscription or resource group.
64	    text: |
65	      az postgres flexible-server create \\
66	        --resource-group testGroup --name testserver \\
67	        --subnet /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{ResourceGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks/{VNetName}/subnets/{SubnetName} \\
68	        --private-dns-zone /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{resourceGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Network/privateDnsZones/testPostgreSQLFlexibleDnsZone.private.postgres.database.azure.com \\
69	        --address-prefixes 172.0.0.0/16 --subnet-prefixes 172.0.0.0/24
70	  - name: >
71	      Create a PostgreSQL flexible server using existing network resources in the same resource group.
72	      The provided subnet should not have any other resource deployed in it and this subnet will be delegated to Microsoft.DBforPostgreSQL/flexibleServers, if not already delegated.
73	      The private DNS zone will be linked to the virtual network if not already linked.
74	    text: >
75	      # create vnet
76	
77	      az network vnet create --resource-group testGroup --name testVnet --location testLocation --address-prefixes 172.0.0.0/16
78

93	        --private-dns-zone /subscriptions/{SubId}/resourceGroups/{testGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Network/privateDnsZones/testDNS.postgres.database.azure.com\\
94

97	        --vnet testVnet --subnet testSubnet --location testLocation \\

122

213	      Create flexible server with custom storage performance tier. Accepted values "P4", "P6", "P10", "P15", "P20", "P30", \\
214	      "P40", "P50", "P60", "P70", "P80". Actual allowed values depend on the --storage-size selection for flexible server creation. \\
215	      Default value for storage performance tier depends on the --storage-size selected for flexible server creation.
216	    text: >
217	      az postgres flexible-server create -g testGroup -n testServer --location testLocation --performance-tier P15
218	
219	  - name: >
220	      Create flexible server with storage auto-grow as Enabled. Accepted values Enabled / Disabled. Default value for storage auto-grow is "Disabled".
221	    text: >
222	      az postgres flexible-server create -g testGroup -n testServer --location testLocation --storage-auto-grow Enabled
223	
224	  - name: >
225	      Create elastic cluster with node count of 5. Default node count is 2 when --cluster-option is "ElasticCluster".
226	    text: >
227	      az postgres flexible-server create -g testGroup -n testCluster --location testLocation --cluster-option ElasticCluster --node-count 5
228	"""

432	type: command
433	short-summary: Start a deployment at subscription scope.
434	long-summary: Please specify only one of --template-file FILE | --template-uri URI | --template-spec to input the ARM template.
435	parameters:
436	  - name: --parameters -p
437	    short-summary: Supply deployment parameter values.
438	    long-summary: >
439	        Parameters may be supplied from a file using the `@{path}` syntax, a JSON string, or as `<KEY=VALUE>` pairs. Parameters are evaluated in order, so when a value is assigned twice, the latter value will be used.
440	        It is recommended that you supply your parameters file first, and then override selectively using KEY=VALUE syntax.
441	  - name: --template-file -f
442	    short-summary: The path to the template file or Bicep file.
443	  - name: --template-uri -u
444	    short-summary: The URI to the template file.
445	  - name: --template-spec -s
446	    short-summary: The template spec resource id.
447	  - name: --location -l
448	    short-summary: The location to store the deployment metadata.
449	  - name: --name -n
450	    short-summary: The deployment name.
451	  - name: --what-if-result-format -r
452	    short-summary: The format of What-If results. Applicable when `--confirm-with-what-if` is set.
453	examples:
454	  - name: Create a deployment at subscription scope from a remote template file, using parameters from a local JSON file.
455	    text: >
456	        az deployment create --location WestUS --template-uri https://myresource/azuredeploy.json --parameters @myparameters.json
457	  - name: Create a deployment at subscription scope from a local template file, using parameters from a JSON string.
458	    text: |
459	        az deployment create --location WestUS --template-file azuredeploy.json  \\
460	            --parameters "{ \\"policyName\\": { \\"value\\": \\"policy2\\" }}"
461	  - name: Create a deployment at subscription scope from a local template, using a parameter file, a remote parameter file, and selectively overriding key/value pairs.
462	    text: >
463	        az deployment create --location WestUS --template-file azuredeploy.json  \\
464	            --parameters @params.json --parameters https://mysite/params.json --parameters MyValue=This MyArray=@array.json
465	  - name: Create a deployment at subscription scope from a template-spec
466	    text: >
467	        az deployment create --location WestUS --template-spec "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.Resources/templateSpecs/myTemplateSpec/versions/1.0"
468	"""

752	helps['deployment group create'] = """
753	type: command
754	short-summary: Start a deployment at resource group.
755	long-summary: Please specify only one of --template-file FILE | --template-uri URI | --template-spec to input the ARM template.
756	parameters:
757	  - name: --parameters -p
758	    short-summary: Supply deployment parameter values.
759	    long-summary: >
760	        Parameters may be supplied from a file using the `@{path}` syntax, a JSON string, or as `<KEY=VALUE>` pairs. Parameters are evaluated in order, so when a value is assigned twice, the latter value will be used.
761	        It is recommended that you supply your parameters file first, and then override selectively using KEY=VALUE syntax. Also note if you are providing a bicepparam file then you can use this argument only once.
762	  - name: --template-file -f
763	    short-summary: The path to the template file or Bicep file.
764	  - name: --template-uri -u
765	    short-summary: The URI to the template file.
766	  - name: --template-spec -s
767	    short-summary: The template spec resource id.
768	  - name: --resource-group -g
769	    short-summary: The resource group to create deployment at.
770	  - name: --name -n
771	    short-summary: The deployment name.
772	  - name: --mode
773	    short-summary: The deployment mode.
774	  - name: --what-if-result-format -r
775	    short-summary: The format of What-If results. Applicable when `--confirm-with-what-if` is set.
776	examples:
777	  - name: Create a deployment at resource group from a remote template file, using parameters from a local JSON file.
778	    text: >
779	        az deployment group create --resource-group testrg --name rollout01 \\
780	            --template-uri https://myresource/azuredeploy.json --parameters @myparameters.json
781	  - name: Create a deployment at resource group from a local template file, using parameters from a JSON string.
782	    text: |
783	        az deployment group create --resource-group testrg --name rollout01 \\
784	            --template-file azuredeploy.json  \\
785	            --parameters '{ \\"policyName\\": { \\"value\\": \\"policy2\\" } }'
786	  - name: Create a deployment at resource group from a local template file, using parameters from an array string.
787	    text: |
788	      az deployment group create --resource-group testgroup --template-file demotemplate.json --parameters exampleString='inline string' exampleArray='("value1", "value2")'
789	  - name: Create a deployment at resource group from a local template, using a parameter file, a remote parameter file, and selectively overriding key/value pairs.
790	    text: >
791	        az deployment group create --resource-group testrg --name rollout01 \\
792	            --template-file azuredeploy.json  --parameters @params.json \\
793	            --parameters https://mysite/params.json --parameters MyValue=This MyArray=@array.json

795	    text: >
796	        az deployment group create --resource-group testrg --template-spec "/subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/testrg/providers/Microsoft.Resources/templateSpecs/myTemplateSpec/versions/1.0"

799	        az deployment group create --resource-group testrg --parameters parameters.bicepparam

814	        Parameters may be supplied from a file using the `@{path}` syntax, a JSON string, or as `<KEY=VALUE>` pairs. Parameters are evaluated in order, so when a value is assigned twice, the latter value will be used.

825	    short-summary: The deployment name.

827	    short-summary: The deployment mode.
828	  - name: --result-format -r

830	examples:
831	  - name: Execute a deployment What-If operation at a resource group.

1723	    text: |
1724	        Valid scopes are management group, subscription, resource group, and resource, for example
1725	           management group:  /providers/Microsoft.Management/managementGroups/MyManagementGroup
1726	           subscription:      /subscriptions/0b1f6471-1bf0-4dda-aec3-111122223333
1727	           resource group:    /subscriptions/0b1f6471-1bf0-4dda-aec3-111122223333/resourceGroups/myGroup
1728	           resource:          /subscriptions/0b1f6471-1bf0-4dda-aec3-111122223333/resourceGroups/myGroup/providers/Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/myVM
1729	             az policy assignment create --scope \\
1730	                "/providers/Microsoft.Management/managementGroups/MyManagementGroup" \\
1731	                    --policy {PolicyName} -p "{ \\"allowedLocations\\": \\
1732	                        { \\"value\\": [ \\"australiaeast\\", \\"eastus\\", \\"japaneast\\" ] } }"
1733	  - name: Create a resource policy assignment and provide rule parameter values.
1734	    text: |
1735	        az policy assignment create --policy {PolicyName} -p "{ \\"allowedLocations\\": \\
1736	            { \\"value\\": [ \\"australiaeast\\", \\"eastus\\", \\"japaneast\\" ] } }"

1739	        az policy assignment create --name myPolicy --policy {PolicyName} --mi-system-assigned --location eastus
1740	  - name: Create a resource policy assignment with a system assigned identity. The identity will have 'Contributor' role access to the subscription.
1741	    text: >
1742	        az policy assignment create --name myPolicy --policy {PolicyName} --mi-system-assigned --identity-scope /subscriptions/xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx --role Contributor --location eastus
1743	  - name: Create a resource policy assignment with a user assigned identity.
1744	    text: >
1745	        az policy assignment create --name myPolicy --policy {PolicyName} -g MyResourceGroup --mi-user-assigned myAssignedId --location westus
1746	  - name: Create a resource policy assignment with an enforcement mode. It indicates whether a policy effect will be enforced or not during assignment creation and update. Please visit https://aka.ms/azure-policyAssignment-enforcement-mode for more information.
1747	    text: >
1748	        az policy assignment create --name myPolicy --policy {PolicyName} --enforcement-mode 'DoNotEnforce'

2236	helps['resource invoke-action'] = """
2237	type: command
2238	short-summary: Invoke an action on the resource.
2239	long-summary: >
2240	    A list of possible actions corresponding to a resource can be found at https://learn.microsoft.com/rest/api/. All POST requests are actions that can be invoked and are specified at the end of the URI path. For instance, to stop a VM, the
2241	    request URI is https://management.azure.com/subscriptions/{SubscriptionId}/resourceGroups/{ResourceGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/{VM}/powerOff?api-version={APIVersion} and the corresponding action is `powerOff`. This can
2242	    be found at https://learn.microsoft.com/rest/api/compute/virtualmachines/virtualmachines-stop.
2243	examples:
2244	  - name: Power-off a vm, specified by Id.
2245	    text: >
2246	        az resource invoke-action --action powerOff \\
2247	          --ids /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{ResourceGroup}/providers/Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/{VMName}
2248	  - name: Capture information for a stopped vm.
2249	    text: >
2250	        az resource invoke-action --action capture \\
2251	          --ids /subscriptions/{SubID}/resourceGroups/{ResourceGroup}/providers/ \\
2252	            Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/{VMName} \\
2253	          --request-body "{ \\"vhdPrefix\\": \\"myPrefix\\", \\"destinationContainerName\\": \\
2254	            \\"myContainer\\", \\"overwriteVhds\\": true }"
2255	  - name: Invoke an action on the resource. (autogenerated)
2256	    text: |
2257	        az resource invoke-action --action capture --name MyResource --resource-group MyResourceGroup --resource-type Microsoft.web/sites
2258	    crafted: true
2259	"""

51	type: command
52	short-summary: Update a database's auditing policy.
53	long-summary: If the policy is being enabled, `--storage-account` or both `--storage-endpoint` and `--storage-key` must be specified.
54	examples:
55	  - name: Enable by storage account name.
56	    text: |
57	        az sql db audit-policy update -g mygroup -s myserver -n mydb --state Enabled \\
58	            --bsts Enabled --storage-account mystorage
59	  - name: Enable by storage endpoint and key.
60	    text: |
61	        az sql db audit-policy update -g mygroup -s myserver -n mydb --state Enabled \\
62	            --bsts Enabled --storage-endpoint https://mystorage.blob.core.windows.net \\
63	            --storage-key MYKEY==
64	  - name: Set the list of audit actions.
65	    text: |
66	        az sql db audit-policy update -g mygroup -s myserver -n mydb \\
67	            --actions FAILED_DATABASE_AUTHENTICATION_GROUP 'UPDATE on database::mydb by public'
68	  - name: Disable an auditing policy.
69	    text: az sql db audit-policy update -g mygroup -s myserver -n mydb --state Disabled
70	  - name: Disable a blob storage auditing policy.
71	    text: az sql db audit-policy update -g mygroup -s myserver -n mydb --bsts Disabled
72	  - name: Enable a log analytics auditing policy.
73	    text: |
74	        az sql db audit-policy update -g mygroup -s myserver -n mydb --state Enabled \\
75	            --lats Enabled --lawri myworkspaceresourceid
76	  - name: Disable a log analytics auditing policy.
77	    text: |
78	        az sql db audit-policy update -g mygroup -s myserver -n mydb
79	            --lats Disabled
80	  - name: Enable an event hub auditing policy.
81	    text: |
82	        az sql db audit-policy update -g mygroup -s myserver -n mydb --state Enabled \\
83	            --event-hub-target-state Enabled \\
84	            --event-hub-authorization-rule-id eventhubauthorizationruleid \\
85	            --event-hub eventhubname
86	  - name: Enable an event hub auditing policy for default event hub.
87	    text: |
88	        az sql db audit-policy update -g mygroup -s myserver -n mydb --state Enabled \\
89	            --event-hub-target-state Enabled \\
90	            --event-hub-authorization-rule-id eventhubauthorizationruleid
91	  - name: Disable an event hub auditing policy.

93	        az sql db audit-policy update -g mygroup -s myserver -n mydb
94	            --event-hub-target-state Disabled

24	helps['sql vm create'] = """
25	type: command
26	short-summary: Creates a SQL virtual machine.
27	parameters:
28	  - name: --name -n
29	    short-summary: Name of the SQL virtual machine. The name of the new SQL virtual machine must be equal to the underlying virtual machine created from SQL marketplace image.
30	examples:
31	  - name: Create a SQL virtual machine with AHUB billing tag.
32	    text: >
33	        az sql vm create -n sqlvm -g myresourcegroup -l eastus --license-type AHUB
34	  - name: Create a SQL virtual machine with DR billing tag.
35	    text: >
36	        az sql vm create -n sqlvm -g myresourcegroup -l eastus --license-type DR
37	  - name: Create a SQL virtual machine with specific sku type and license type.
38	    text: >
39	        az sql vm create -n sqlvm -g myresourcegroup -l eastus --image-sku Enterprise --license-type AHUB
40	  - name: Create a SQL virtual machine with least privilege mode enabled.
41	    text: >
42	        az sql vm create -n sqlvm -g myresourcegroup -l eastus --least-privilege-mode Enabled --sql-mgmt-type Full
43	  - name: Create a SQL virtual machine with NoAgent type, only valid for EOS SQL 2008 and SQL 2008 R2.
44	    text: >
45	        az sql vm create -n sqlvm -g myresourcegroup -l eastus --license-type AHUB --sql-mgmt-type NoAgent --image-sku Enterprise --image-offer SQL2008-WS2008R2
46	  - name: Enable R services in SQL2016 onwards.
47	    text: >
48	        az sql vm create -n sqlvm -g myresourcegroup -l eastus --license-type PAYG --sql-mgmt-type Full --enable-r-services true
49	  - name: Create SQL virtual machine and configure auto backup settings.
50	    text: >
51	        az sql vm create -n sqlvm -g myresourcegroup -l eastus --license-type PAYG --sql-mgmt-type Full --backup-schedule-type manual --full-backup-frequency Weekly --full-backup-start-hour 2 --full-backup-duration 2 --sa-key {storageKey} --storage-account 'https://storageacc.blob.core.windows.net/' --retention-period 30 --log-backup-frequency 60
52	  - name: Create SQL virtual machine and configure auto patching settings.
53	    text: >
54	        az sql vm create -n sqlvm -g myresourcegroup -l eastus --license-type PAYG --sql-mgmt-type Full --day-of-week sunday --maintenance-window-duration 60 --maintenance-window-start-hour 2
55	  - name: Create SQL virtual machine and configure SQL connectivity settings.
56	    text: >
57	        az sql vm create -n sqlvm -g myresourcegroup -l eastus --license-type PAYG --sql-mgmt-type Full --connectivity-type private --port 1433 --sql-auth-update-username {newlogin} --sql-auth-update-pwd {sqlpassword}
58	"""

789	parameters:
790	  - name: --source-uri -u
791	    type: string
792	    short-summary: >
793	        A URL of up to 2 KB in length that specifies an Azure file or blob.
794	        The value should be URL-encoded as it would appear in a request URI.
795	        If the source is in another account, the source must either be public
796	        or must be authenticated via a shared access signature. If the source
797	        is public, no authentication is required.
798	        Examples:
799	        `https://myaccount.blob.core.windows.net/mycontainer/myblob`,
800	        `https://myaccount.blob.core.windows.net/mycontainer/myblob?snapshot=<DateTime>`,
801	        `https://otheraccount.blob.core.windows.net/mycontainer/myblob?sastoken`
802	  - name: --destination-if-modified-since
803	    type: string
804	    short-summary: >
805	        A DateTime value. Azure expects the date value passed in to be UTC.
806	        If timezone is included, any non-UTC datetimes will be converted to UTC.
807	        If a date is passed in without timezone info, it is assumed to be UTC.
808	        Specify this conditional header to copy the blob only
809	        if the destination blob has been modified since the specified date/time.
810	        If the destination blob has not been modified, the Blob service returns
811	        status code 412 (Precondition Failed).
812	  - name: --destination-if-unmodified-since
813	    type: string
814	    short-summary: >
815	        A DateTime value. Azure expects the date value passed in to be UTC.
816	        If timezone is included, any non-UTC datetimes will be converted to UTC.
817	        If a date is passed in without timezone info, it is assumed to be UTC.
818	        Specify this conditional header to copy the blob only
819	        if the destination blob has not been modified since the specified
820	        date/time. If the destination blob has been modified, the Blob service
821	        returns status code 412 (Precondition Failed).
822	  - name: --source-if-modified-since
823	    type: string
824	    short-summary: >
825	        A DateTime value. Azure expects the date value passed in to be UTC.
826	        If timezone is included, any non-UTC datetimes will be converted to UTC.
827	        If a date is passed in without timezone info, it is assumed to be UTC.

832	    short-summary: >
833	        A DateTime value. Azure expects the date value passed in to be UTC.
834	        If timezone is included, any non-UTC datetimes will be converted to UTC.
835	        If a date is passed in without timezone info, it is assumed to be UTC.
836	        Specify this conditional header to copy the blob only if the source blob

931	    long-summary: If this is specified, it will ignore all the Precondition Arguments that include --if-modified-since and --if-unmodified-since. So the file(s) will be deleted with the command without --dryrun may be different from the result list with --dryrun flag on.
932	  - name: --if-match
933	    type: string
934	    short-summary: An ETag value, or the wildcard character (*). Specify this header to perform the operation only if the resource's ETag matches the value specified.
935	  - name: --if-none-match

937	    short-summary: An ETag value, or the wildcard character (*).
938	    long-summary: Specify this header to perform the operation only if the resource's ETag does not match the value specified. Specify the wildcard character (*) to perform the operation only if the resource does not exist, and fail the operation if it does exist.
939	examples:
940	  - name: Delete all blobs ending with ".py" in a container that have not been modified for 10 days.
941	    text: |
942	        date=`date -d "10 days ago" '+%Y-%m-%dT%H:%MZ'`

1024	helps['storage blob incremental-copy start'] = """
1025	type: command
1026	short-summary: Copies an incremental copy of a blob asynchronously.
1027	long-summary: This operation returns a copy operation properties object, including a copy ID you can use to check or abort the copy operation. The Blob service copies blobs on a best-effort basis. The source blob for an incremental copy operation must be a page blob. Call get_blob_properties on the destination blob to check the status of the copy operation. The final blob will be committed when the copy completes.
1028	parameters:
1029	  - name: --source-uri -u
1030	    short-summary: >
1031	        A URL of up to 2 KB in length that specifies an Azure page blob.
1032	        The value should be URL-encoded as it would appear in a request URI.
1033	        The copy source must be a snapshot and include a valid SAS token or be public.
1034	        Example:
1035	        `https://myaccount.blob.core.windows.net/mycontainer/myblob?snapshot=<DateTime>&sastoken`
1036	examples:
1037	  - name: Upload all files that end with .py unless blob exists and has been modified since given date.
1038	    text: az storage blob incremental-copy start --source-container MySourceContainer --source-blob MyBlob --source-account-name MySourceAccount --source-account-key MySourceKey --source-snapshot MySnapshot --destination-container MyDestinationContainer --destination-blob MyDestinationBlob
1039	  - name: Copies an incremental copy of a blob asynchronously. (autogenerated)
1040	    text: |
1041	        az storage blob incremental-copy start --account-key 00000000 --account-name MyAccount --destination-blob MyDestinationBlob --destination-container MyDestinationContainer --source-account-key MySourceKey --source-account-name MySourceAccount --source-blob MyBlob --source-container MySourceContainer --source-snapshot MySnapshot

1262	    short-summary: Default to 'page' for *.vhd files, or 'block' otherwise.

1270	  - name: Upload to a blob with blob sas url.

1272	  - name: Upload a file to a storage blob. (autogenerated)
1273	    text: |
1274	        az storage blob upload --account-name mystorageaccount --account-key 0000-0000 --container-name mycontainer --file /path/to/file --name myblob
1275	    crafted: true
1276	  - name: Upload a string to a blob.
1277	    text: az storage blob upload --data "teststring" -c mycontainer -n myblob --account-name mystorageaccount --account-key 0000-0000
1278	  - name: Upload to a through pipe.
1279	    text: |
1280	        echo $data | az storage blob upload --data @- -c mycontainer -n myblob --account-name mystorageaccount --account-key 0000-0000
