1284	type: command
1285	short-summary: Upload files from a local directory to a blob container.
1286	parameters:
1287	  - name: --source -s
1288	    type: string
1289	    short-summary: The directory where the files to be uploaded are located.
1290	  - name: --destination -d
1291	    type: string
1292	    short-summary: The blob container where the files will be uploaded.
1293	    long-summary: The destination can be the container URL or the container name. When the destination is the container URL, the storage account name will be parsed from the URL.
1294	  - name: --pattern
1295	    type: string
1296	    short-summary: The pattern used for globbing files or blobs in the source. The supported patterns are '*', '?', '[seq]', and '[!seq]'. For more information, please refer to https://docs.python.org/3/library/fnmatch.html.
1297	    long-summary: When you use '*' in --pattern, it will match any character including the the directory separator '/'.
1298	  - name: --dryrun
1299	    type: bool
1300	    short-summary: Show the summary of the operations to be taken instead of actually uploading the file(s).
1301	  - name: --if-match
1302	    type: string
1303	    short-summary: An ETag value, or the wildcard character (*). Specify this header to perform the operation only if the resource's ETag matches the value specified.
1304	  - name: --if-none-match
1305	    type: string
1306	    short-summary: An ETag value, or the wildcard character (*).
1307	    long-summary: Specify this header to perform the operation only if the resource's ETag does not match the value specified. Specify the wildcard character (*) to perform the operation only if the resource does not exist, and fail the operation if it does exist.
1308	  - name: --validate-content
1309	    short-summary: Specifies that an MD5 hash shall be calculated for each chunk of the blob and verified by the service when the chunk has arrived.
1310	  - name: --type -t
1311	    short-summary: Defaults to 'page' for *.vhd files, or 'block' otherwise. The setting will override blob types for every file.
1312	  - name: --maxsize-condition
1313	    short-summary: The max length in bytes permitted for an append blob.
1314	  - name: --lease-id
1315	    short-summary: The active lease id for the blob
1316	examples:
1317	  - name: Upload all files that end with .py unless blob exists and has been modified since given date.
1318	    text: |
1319	        az storage blob upload-batch -d mycontainer --account-name mystorageaccount --account-key 00000000 -s <path-to-directory> --pattern "*.py" --if-unmodified-since 2018-08-27T20:51Z
1320	  - name: Upload all files from local path directory to a container named "mycontainer".
1321	    text: |
1322	        az storage blob upload-batch -d mycontainer -s <path-to-directory>
1323	  - name: Upload all files with the format 'cli-2018-xx-xx.txt' or 'cli-2019-xx-xx.txt' in local path directory.
1324	    text: |
1325	        az storage blob upload-batch -d mycontainer -s <path-to-directory> --pattern "cli-201[89]-??-??.txt"
1326	  - name: Upload all files with the format 'cli-201x-xx-xx.txt' except cli-2018-xx-xx.txt' and 'cli-2019-xx-xx.txt' in a container.
1327	    text: |
1328	        az storage blob upload-batch -d mycontainer -s <path-to-directory> --pattern "cli-201[!89]-??-??.txt"

1675	type: command
1676	short-summary: Copy files or directories to or from Azure storage.
1677	examples:
1678	  - name: Upload a single file to Azure Blob using url.
1679	    text: az storage copy -s /path/to/file.txt -d https://[account].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/blob]
1680	  - name: Upload a single file to Azure Blob using account name and container name.
1681	    text: az storage copy -s /path/to/file.txt --destination-account-name mystorageaccount --destination-container mycontainer
1682	  - name: Upload a single file to Azure Blob with MD5 hash of the file content and save it as the blob's Content-MD5 property.
1683	    text: az storage copy -s /path/to/file.txt -d https://[account].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/blob] --put-md5
1684	  - name: Upload an entire directory to Azure Blob using url.
1685	    text: az storage copy -s /path/to/dir -d https://[account].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/directory] --recursive
1686	  - name: Upload an entire directory to Azure Blob using account name and container name.
1687	    text: az storage copy -s /path/to/dir --destination-account-name mystorageaccount --destination-container mycontainer --recursive
1688	  - name: Upload a set of files to Azure Blob using wildcards with url.
1689	    text: az storage copy -s /path/*foo/*bar/*.pdf -d https://[account].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/directory]
1690	  - name: Upload a set of files to Azure Blob using wildcards with account name and container name.
1691	    text: az storage copy -s /path/*foo/*bar/*.pdf --destination-account-name mystorageaccount --destination-container mycontainer
1692	  - name: Upload files and directories to Azure Blob using wildcards with url.
1693	    text: az storage copy -s /path/*foo/*bar* -d https://[account].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/directory] --recursive
1694	  - name: Upload files and directories to Azure Blob using wildcards with account name and container name.
1695	    text: az storage copy -s /path/*foo/*bar* --destination-account-name mystorageaccount --destination-container mycontainer --recursive
1696	  - name: Download a single file from Azure Blob using url, and you can also specify your storage account and container information as above.
1697	    text: az storage copy -s https://[account].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/blob] -d /path/to/file.txt
1698	  - name: Download an entire directory from Azure Blob, and you can also specify your storage account and container information as above.
1699	    text: az storage copy -s https://[account].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/directory] -d /path/to/dir --recursive
1700	  - name: Download a subset of containers within a storage account by using a wildcard symbol (*) in the container name, and you can also specify your storage account and container information as above.
1701	    text: az storage copy -s https://[account].blob.core.windows.net/[container*name] -d /path/to/dir --recursive
1702	  - name: Download a subset of files from Azure Blob. (Only jpg files and file names don't start with test will be included.)
1703	    text: az storage copy -s https://[account].blob.core.windows.net/[container] --include-pattern "*.jpg" --exclude-pattern test* -d /path/to/dir --recursive
1704	  - name: Copy a single blob to another blob, and you can also specify the storage account and container information of source and destination as above.
1705	    text: az storage copy -s https://[srcaccount].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/blob] -d https://[destaccount].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/blob]
1706	  - name: Copy an entire account data from blob account to another blob account, and you can also specify the storage account and container information of source and destination as above.
1707	    text: az storage copy -s https://[srcaccount].blob.core.windows.net -d https://[destaccount].blob.core.windows.net --recursive
1708	  - name: Copy a single object from S3 with access key to blob, and you can also specify your storage account and container information as above.
1709	    text: az storage copy -s https://s3.amazonaws.com/[bucket]/[object] -d https://[destaccount].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/blob]
1710	  - name: Copy an entire directory from S3 with access key to blob virtual directory, and you can also specify your storage account and container information as above.
1711	    text: az storage copy -s https://s3.amazonaws.com/[bucket]/[folder] -d https://[destaccount].blob.core.windows.net/[container]/[path/to/directory] --recursive
1712	  - name: Copy all buckets in S3 service with access key to blob account, and you can also specify your storage account information as above.
1713	    text: az storage copy -s https://s3.amazonaws.com/ -d https://[destaccount].blob.core.windows.net --recursive
1714	  - name: Copy all buckets in a S3 region with access key to blob account, and you can also specify your storage account information as above.
1715	    text: az storage copy -s https://s3-[region].amazonaws.com/ -d https://[destaccount].blob.core.windows.net --recursive
1716	  - name: Upload a single file to Azure File Share using url.
1717	    text: az storage copy -s /path/to/file.txt -d https://[account].file.core.windows.net/[share]/[path/to/file]
1718	  - name: Upload a single file to Azure File Share using account name and share name.
1719	    text: az storage copy -s /path/to/file.txt --destination-account-name mystorageaccount --destination-share myshare

1721	    text: az storage copy -s /path/to/dir -d https://[account].file.core.windows.net/[share]/[path/to/directory] --recursive
1722	  - name: Upload an entire directory to Azure File Share using account name and container name.
1723	    text: az storage copy -s /path/to/dir --destination-account-name mystorageaccount --destination-share myshare --recursive
1724	  - name: Upload a set of files to Azure File Share using wildcards with account name and share name.
1725	    text: az storage copy -s /path/*foo/*bar/*.pdf --destination-account-name mystorageaccount --destination-share myshare
1726	  - name: Upload files and directories to Azure File Share using wildcards with url.
1727	    text: az storage copy -s /path/*foo/*bar* -d https://[account].file.core.windows.net/[share]/[path/to/directory] --recursive
1728	  - name: Upload files and directories to Azure File Share using wildcards with account name and share name.
1729	    text: az storage copy -s /path/*foo/*bar* --destination-account-name mystorageaccount --destination-share myshare --recursive
1730	  - name: Download a single file from Azure File Share using url, and you can also specify your storage account and share information as above.
1731	    text: az storage copy -s https://[account].file.core.windows.net/[share]/[path/to/file] -d /path/to/file.txt
1732	  - name: Download an entire directory from Azure File Share, and you can also specify your storage account and share information as above.

1931	type: command
1932	short-summary: Copy a file asynchronously.
1933	parameters:
1934	  - name: --source-uri -u
1935	    type: string
1936	    short-summary: >
1937	        A URL of up to 2 KB in length that specifies an Azure file or blob.
1938	        The value should be URL-encoded as it would appear in a request URI.
1939	        If the source is in another account, the source must either be public
1940	        or must be authenticated via a shared access signature. If the source
1941	        is public, no authentication is required.
1942	        Examples:
1943	        https://myaccount.file.core.windows.net/myshare/mydir/myfile
1944	        https://otheraccount.file.core.windows.net/myshare/mydir/myfile?sastoken.
1945	examples:
1946	    - name: Copy a file asynchronously.
1947	      text: |
1948	        az storage file copy start --source-account-name srcaccount --source-account-key 00000000 --source-path <srcpath-to-file> --source-share srcshare --destination-path <destpath-to-file> --destination-share destshare --account-name destaccount --account-key 00000000
1949	    - name: Copy a file asynchronously from source uri to destination storage account with sas token.
1950	      text: |
1951	        az storage file copy start --source-uri "https://srcaccount.file.core.windows.net/myshare/mydir/myfile?<sastoken>" --destination-path <destpath-to-file> --destination-share destshare --account-name destaccount --sas-token <destination-sas>
1952	    - name: Copy a file asynchronously from file snapshot to destination storage account with sas token.
1953	      text: |
1954	        az storage file copy start --source-account-name srcaccount --source-account-key 00000000 --source-path <srcpath-to-file> --source-share srcshare --file-snapshot "2020-03-02T13:51:54.0000000Z" --destination-path <destpath-to-file> --destination-share destshare --account-name destaccount --sas-token <destination-sas>
1955	    - name: Copy a file with the source file-mode, group, owner.
1956	      text: |
1957	        az storage file copy start --source-account-name srcaccount --source-path srcpath --source-share srcshare --destination-path dstpath --destination-share dstshare --owner-copy-mode Source --file-mode-copy-mode Source
1958	    - name: Copy a file with the overridden file-mode, group, owner.
1959	      text: |
1960	        az storage file copy start --source-account-name srcaccount --source-path srcpath --source-share srcshare --destination-path dstpath --destination-share dstshare --owner-copy-mode Override --file-mode-copy-mode Override --file-mode rw-rw-rw- --owner 4 --group 5

2048	    short-summary: The local directory where the files are downloaded to. This directory must already exist.
2049	  - name: --pattern
2050	    type: string
2051	    short-summary: The pattern used for file globbing. The supported patterns are '*', '?', '[seq]', and '[!seq]'. For more information, please refer to https://docs.python.org/3/library/fnmatch.html.
2052	    long-summary: When you use '*' in --pattern, it will match any character including the the directory separator '/'.
2053	  - name: --dryrun
2054	    type: bool
2055	    short-summary: List the files and blobs to be downloaded. No actual data transfer will occur.
2056	  - name: --max-connections
2057	    type: integer
2058	    short-summary: The maximum number of parallel connections to use. Default value is 1.
2059	  - name: --snapshot
2060	    type: string
2061	    short-summary: A string that represents the snapshot version, if applicable.
2062	  - name: --validate-content
2063	    type: bool
2064	    short-summary: If set, calculates an MD5 hash for each range of the file for validation.
2065	    long-summary: >
2066	        The storage service checks the hash of the content that has arrived is identical to the hash that was sent.
2067	        This is mostly valuable for detecting bitflips during transfer if using HTTP instead of HTTPS. This hash is not stored.
2068	examples:
2069	  - name: Download files from an Azure Storage File Share to a local directory in a batch operation. (autogenerated)
2070	    text: |
2071	        az storage file download-batch --account-key 00000000 --account-name MyAccount --destination . --no-progress --source /path/to/file
2072	    crafted: true
2073	"""

2262	helps['storage fs access set'] = """
2263	type: command
2264	short-summary: Set the access control properties of a path(directory or file) in Azure Data Lake Storage Gen2 account.
2265	parameters:
2266	    - name: --acl
2267	      short-summary: Invalid in conjunction with acl. POSIX access control rights on files and directories in the format "[scope:][type]:[id]:[permissions]". e.g. "user::rwx,group::r--,other::---,mask::rwx".
2268	      long-summary: >
2269	        The value is a comma-separated list of access control entries. Each access control entry (ACE) consists of a scope,
2270	        a type, a user or group identifier, and permissions in the format "[scope:][type]:[id]:[permissions]".
2271	        The scope must be "default" to indicate the ACE belongs to the default ACL for a directory;
2272	        otherwise scope is implicit and the ACE belongs to the access ACL. There are four ACE types:
2273	        "user" grants rights to the owner or a named user, "group" grants rights to the owning group
2274	        or a named group, "mask" restricts rights granted to named users and the members of groups,
2275	        and "other" grants rights to all users not found in any of the other entries.
2276	        The user or group identifier is omitted for entries of type "mask" and "other".
2277	        The user or group identifier is also omitted for the owner and owning group.
2278	        For example, the following ACL grants read, write, and execute rights to the file owner an
2279	        john.doe@contoso, the read right to the owning group, and nothing to everyone else:
2280	        "user::rwx,user:john.doe@contoso:rwx,group::r--,other::---,mask::rwx".
2281	        For more information, please refer to https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/storage/blobs/data-lake-storage-access-control.
2282	    - name: --permissions
2283	      short-summary: >
2284	        Invalid in conjunction with acl. POSIX access permissions for the file owner, the file owning group, and others.
2285	        Each class may be granted read(r), write(w), or execute(x) permission. Both symbolic (rwxrw-rw-) and 4-digit octal
2286	        notation (e.g. 0766) are supported.'
2287	    - name: --owner
2288	      short-summary: >
2289	        The owning user of the file or directory. The user Azure Active Directory object ID or user principal name to
2290	        set as the owner. For more information, please refer to
2291	        https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/storage/blobs/data-lake-storage-access-control#the-owning-user.
2292	    - name: --group
2293	      short-summary: >
2294	        The owning group of the file or directory. The group Azure Active Directory object ID or user principal name to
2295	        set as the owning group. For more information, please refer to
2296	        https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/storage/blobs/data-lake-storage-access-control#changing-the-owning-group.
2297	examples:
2298	    - name: Set the access control list of a path.
2299	      text: az storage fs access set --acl "user::rwx,group::r--,other::---" -p dir -f myfilesystem --account-name mystorageaccount --account-key 0000-0000
2300	    - name: Set permissions of a path.
2301	      text: az storage fs access set --permissions "rwxrwx---" -p dir -f myfilesystem --account-name mystorageaccount --account-key 0000-0000
2302	    - name: Set owner of a path.
2303	      text: az storage fs access set --owner example@microsoft.com -p dir -f myfilesystem --account-name mystorageaccount --account-key 0000-0000
2304	    - name: Set owning group of a path.
2305	      text: az storage fs access set --group 68390a19-a897-236b-b453-488abf67b4dc -p dir -f myfilesystem --account-name mystorageaccount --account-key 0000-0000
2306	"""

278	helps['synapse sql audit-policy update'] = """
279	type: command
280	short-summary: Update a SQL's auditing policy.
281	long-summary: If the policy is being enabled, `--storage-account` or both `--storage-endpoint` and `--storage-key` must be specified.
282	examples:
283	  - name: Enable by storage account name.
284	    text: |
285	        az synapse sql audit-policy update --workspace-name testsynapseworkspace --resource-group rg --state Enabled \\
286	            --blob-storage-target-state Enabled --storage-account mystorage
287	  - name: Enable by storage endpoint and key.
288	    text: |
289	        az synapse sql audit-policy update --workspace-name testsynapseworkspace --resource-group rg --state Enabled \\
290	            --blob-storage-target-state Enabled --storage-endpoint https://mystorage.blob.core.windows.net \\
291	            --storage-key MYKEY==
292	  - name: Set the list of audit actions.
293	    text: |
294	        az synapse sql audit-policy update --workspace-name testsynapseworkspace --resource-group rg \\
295	        --actions SUCCESSFUL_DATABASE_AUTHENTICATION_GROUP 'UPDATE on database::mydb by public'
296	  - name: Disable an auditing policy.
297	    text: |-
298	        az synapse sql audit-policy update --workspace-name testsynapseworkspace --resource-group rg \\
299	        --state Disabled
300	  - name: Disable a blob storage auditing policy.
301	    text: |-
302	        az synapse sql audit-policy update --workspace-name testsynapseworkspace --resource-group rg \\
303	        --blob-storage-target-state Disabled
304	  - name: Enable a log analytics auditing policy.
305	    text: |
306	        az synapse sql audit-policy update --resource-group mygroup --workspace-name myws --state Enabled \\
307	            --log-analytics-target-state Enabled --log-analytics-workspace-resource-id myworkspaceresourceid
308	  - name: Disable a log analytics auditing policy.
309	    text: |
310	        az synapse sql audit-policy update --resource-group mygroup --workspace-name myws --state Enabled
311	            --log-analytics-target-state Disabled
312	  - name: Enable an event hub auditing policy.
313	    text: |
314	        az synapse sql audit-policy update --resource-group mygroup --workspace-name myws --state Enabled \\
315	            --event-hub-target-state Enabled \\
316	            --event-hub-authorization-rule-id eventhubauthorizationruleid \\
317	            --event-hub eventhubname
318	  - name: Enable an event hub auditing policy for default event hub.
319	    text: |
320	        az synapse sql audit-policy update --resource-group mygroup --workspace-name myws --state Enabled \\
321	            --event-hub-target-state Enabled \\
322	            --event-hub-authorization-rule-id eventhubauthorizationruleid
323	  - name: Disable an event hub auditing policy.
324	    text: |
325	        az synapse sql audit-policy update --resource-group mygroup --workspace-name myws
326	           --state Enabled --event-hub-target-state Disabled
327	"""

583	    text: |-
584	        az synapse sql pool threat-policy update --name sqlpool --workspace-name testsynapseworkspace --resource-group rg \\
585	        --disabled-alerts Sql_Injection_Vulnerability Access_Anomaly --security-alert-policy-name threatpolicy
586	  - name: Configure email recipients for a policy.
587	    text: |-
588	        az synapse sql pool threat-policy update --name sqlpool --workspace-name testsynapseworkspace --resource-group rg \\

590	        --security-alert-policy-name threatpolicy
591	  - name: Disable a threat policy.
592	    text: |-
593	        az synapse sql pool threat-policy update --name sqlpool --workspace-name testsynapseworkspace --resource-group rg \\
594	        --state Disabled --security-alert-policy-name threatpolicy
595	"""

11	type: command
12	short-summary: Invoke a custom request.
13	long-summary: >
14	    This command automatically authenticates using the logged-in credential: If Authorization header is not set, it
15	    attaches header `Authorization: Bearer <token>`, where `<token>` is retrieved from AAD. The target resource of the
16	    token is derived from --url if --url starts with an endpoint from `az cloud show --query endpoints`. You may also
17	    use --resource for a custom resource.
18	
19	
20	    If Content-Type header is not set and --body is a valid JSON string, Content-Type header will default to
21	    application/json.
22	
23	
24	    For passing JSON in PowerShell, see https://github.com/Azure/azure-cli/blob/dev/doc/quoting-issues-with-powershell.md
25	examples:
26	- name: Get Audit log through Microsoft Graph
27	  text: >
28	      az rest --method get --url https://graph.microsoft.com/beta/auditLogs/directoryAudits
29	- name: Update a Azure Active Directory Graph User's display name
30	  text: |
31	      (Bash or CMD)
32	      az rest --method patch --url "https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/users/johndoe@azuresdkteam.onmicrosoft.com" --body "{\\"displayName\\": \\"johndoe2\\"}"
33	
34	      (Bash)
35	      az rest --method patch --url "https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/users/johndoe@azuresdkteam.onmicrosoft.com" --body '{"displayName": "johndoe2"}'
36	
37	      (PowerShell)
38	      az rest --method patch --url "https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/users/johndoe@azuresdkteam.onmicrosoft.com" --body '{\\"displayName\\": \\"johndoe2\\"}'
39	- name: Get a virtual machine
40	  text: >
41	      az rest --method get --uri /subscriptions/{subscriptionId}/resourceGroups/{resourceGroupName}/providers/Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/{vmName}?api-version=2019-03-01
42	- name: Create a public IP address from body.json file
43	  text: >
44	      az rest --method put --url https://management.azure.com/subscriptions/{subscriptionId}/resourceGroups/{resourceGroupName}/providers/Microsoft.Network/publicIPAddresses/{publicIpAddressName}?api-version=2019-09-01 --body @body.json

147	
148	  - name: >
149	        [Advanced] Create an image template with multiple customizers and distributors using the CLI's object cache via --defer. Supports features such as: customizer and output names, powershell exit codes, inline scripts, windows restart, file customizers, artifact tags and vhd output distributors.
150	    text: |
151	        script="https://my-script-url.com/customize_script.ps1"
152	        imagesource="MicrosoftWindowsServer:WindowsServer:2019-Datacenter:2019.0.20190214"
153	
154	        # create and update template object in local cli cache. Defers put request to ARM
155	        # Cache object ttl set via az configure.
156	        az image builder create --image-source $imagesource -n myTemplate \\
157	            -g myGroup --scripts $script --identity myIdentity --defer
158	
159	        # add customizers
160	        az image builder customizer add -n myTemplate -g myGroup  \\
161	            --customizer-name myPwshScript --exit-codes 0 1 --inline-script \\
162	            "mkdir c:\\buildActions" "echo Azure-Image-Builder-Was-Here \\
163	             > c:\\buildActions\\Output.txt" --type powershell --defer
164	
165	        az image builder customizer add -n myTemplate -g myGroup \\
166	            --customizer-name myFileCustomizer --type file \\
167	            --file-source "https://my-file-source.net/file.txt"  \\
168	            --dest-path "c:\\buildArtifacts\\file.txt" --defer
169	
170	        # add distributors
171	        az image builder output add -n myTemplate -g myGroup --is-vhd \\
172	            --output-name myWinImageVhd --artifact-tags "is_vhd=True" --defer
173	
174	        az image builder output add -n myTemplate -g myGroup \\
175	            --output-name myWinImageManaged --managed-image winImage \\
176	            --managed-image-location eastus \\
177	            --artifact-tags "is_vhd=False" --defer
178	
179	        # Stop deferring put request to ARM. Create the template from the object cache.
180	        # Cache object will be deleted.
181	        az image builder update -n myTemplate -g myGroup
182	"""
183

724	helps['sig image-version create'] = """
725	type: command
726	short-summary: create a new image version
727	long-summary: this operation might take a long time depending on the replicate region number. Use "--no-wait" is advised.
728	examples:
729	  - name: Add a new image version from a virtual machine
730	    text: |
731	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
732	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
733	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
734	        --virtual-machine /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/MyVM
735	  - name: Add a new image version from a managed image
736	    text: |
737	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
738	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
739	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
740	        --managed-image /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/images/MyManagedImage
741	  - name: Add a new image version from another image version
742	    text: |
743	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
744	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
745	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
746	        --image-version /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/MyGallery/images/MyImageDefinition/versions/1.0.0
747	  - name: Add a new image version from a managed disk
748	    text: |
749	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
750	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
751	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
752	        --os-snapshot /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/disks/MyOSDisk
753	  - name: Add a new image version from a managed disk and add additional data disks
754	    text: |
755	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
756	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
757	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
758	        --os-snapshot /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/disks/MyOSDisk \\
759	        --data-snapshots /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/disks/MyDataDisk \\
760	        --data-snapshot-luns 0
761	  - name: Add a new image version from a snapshot of an OS disk.
762	    text: |
763	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
764	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
765	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
766	        --os-snapshot /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/snapshots/MyOsDiskSnapshot
767	  - name: Add a new image version from a snapshot of an OS disk and add additional snapshots as data disks
768	    text: |
769	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
770	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
771	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
772	        --os-snapshot /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/snapshots/MyOsDiskSnapshot \\
773	        --data-snapshots /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/snapshots/MyDiskSnapshot \\
774	        --data-snapshot-luns 0
775	  - name: Add a new image version from a VHD of an OS disk.
776	    text: |
777	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
778	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
779	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
780	        --os-vhd-storage-account /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/mystorageaccount \\
781	        --os-vhd-uri https://mystorageaccount.blob.core.windows.net/container/path_to_vhd_file
782	  - name: Add a new image version from a VHD of an OS disk and add additional VHDs as data disks
783	    text: |
784	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
785	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
786	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
787	        --os-vhd-storage-account /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/mystorageaccount \\
788	        --os-vhd-uri https://mystorageaccount.blob.core.windows.net/container/path_to_vhd_file \\
789	        --data-vhds-sa /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/myotherstorageaccount \\
790	        --data-vhds-uris https://myotherstorageaccount.blob.core.windows.net/container/path_to_vhd_file \\
791	        --data-vhds-luns 0
792	  - name: You can combine snapshots, managed disks, and VHDs to create a new image version. Add a new image version using a VHD as the OS disk and a managed disk and a snapshot as data disks.
793	    text: |
794	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
795	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
796	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
797	        --os-vhd-storage-account /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/mystorageaccount \\
798	        --os-vhd-uri https://mystorageaccount.blob.core.windows.net/container/path_to_vhd_file \\
799	        --data-snapshots /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/disks/MyDataDisk subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/snapshots/MyDiskSnapshot \\
800	        --data-snapshot-luns 0 1
801	  - name: Add a new image version and copy it to additional regions. The home location for the source of the image version must be included in the list of target regions. For each additional region, you can specify a different replica count and storage account type. Otherwise, the region will inherit from the global. The default replica count is 1 and the default storage account type is Standard LRS. In this example, eastus2 will have one replica stored on Standard ZRS storage, ukwest will have 3 replicas stored on Standard ZRS storage, southindia will have one replica stored on Standard LRS storage, and brazilsouth will have 2 replicas stored on Standard LRS storage.
802	    text: |
803	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
804	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
805	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 --replica-count 1 \\
806	        --storage-account-type Standard_ZRS --managed-image image-name \\
807	        --target-regions eastus2 ukwest=3 southindia=standard_lrs \\
808	        brazilsouth=2=standard_lrs
809	  - name: Add a new image version with encryption using a disk encryption set. Encryption is applied to each disk that is a part of the image version.
810	    text: |
811	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
812	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
813	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
814	        --virtual-machine /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/MyVM \\
815	        --target-regions westus=2=standard eastus \\
816	        --target-region-encryption WestUSDiskEncryptionSet1,0,WestUSDiskEncryptionSet2 \\
817	        EastUSDiskEncryptionSet1,0,EastUSDiskEncryptionSet2
818	  - name: Add a new image version and copy it to extended locations.
819	    text: |
820	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
821	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
822	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 --replica-count 1 \\
823	        --storage-account-type Standard_ZRS --managed-image image-name \\
824	        --target-edge-zones westus=microsoftlosangeles1 eastus=microsoftlosangeles2=1 \\
825	        brazilsouth=2=standard_lrs
826	  - name: Add a new image version and copy it to extended locations with encryption using a disk encryption set.
827	    text: |
828	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
829	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
830	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
831	        --virtual-machine /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/MyVM \\
832	        --target-edge-zones westus=microsoftlosangeles1 \\
833	        --target-edge-zone-encryption microsoftlosangeles1,WestUSDiskEncryptionSet1,0,WestUSDiskEncryptionSet2
834	  - name: Add a new image version and don't wait on it. Later you can invoke "az sig image-version wait" command when ready to create a vm from the gallery image version
835	    text: |
836	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
837	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
838	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
839	        --virtual-machine /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/MyVM \\
840	        --no-wait
841	  - name: Add a new image version but remove it from consideration as latest version in its image definition
842	    text: |
843	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
844	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
845	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
846	        --virtual-machine /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/MyVM \\
847	        --exclude-from-latest true
848	  - name: Add a new image version and set its end-of-life date. The image version can still be used to create a virtual machine after its end-of-life date.
849	    text: |
850	        az sig image-version create --resource-group MyResourceGroup \\
851	        --gallery-name MyGallery --gallery-image-definition MyImage \\
852	        --gallery-image-version 1.0.0 \\
853	        --virtual-machine /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-00000000xxxx/resourceGroups/imageGroups/providers/Microsoft.Compute/virtualMachines/MyVM \\
854	        --end-of-life-date 2024-08-02T00:00:00+00:00
855	"""

1160	short-summary: Create an Azure Virtual Machine.
1161	long-summary: 'For an end-to-end tutorial, see https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/virtual-machines/linux/quick-create-cli.'
1162	parameters:

1164	    type: string

1167	        Please use the image alias including the version of the distribution you want to use. For example: please use Debian11 instead of Debian.'
1168	        This parameter is required unless using `--attach-os-disk.` Valid URN format: "Publisher:Offer:Sku:Version". For more information, see https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/virtual-machines/linux/cli-ps-findimage

1175	      - az vm list-sizes
1176	  - name: --ssh-key-values
1177	    short-summary: Space-separated list of SSH public keys or public key file paths.
1178	  - name: --computer-name
1179	    short-summary: The host OS name of the virtual machine. Defaults to the name of the VM.
1180	examples:
1181	  - name: Create a default Ubuntu2204 VM with automatic SSH authentication.
1182	    text: >

1184	  - name: Create a default RedHat VM with automatic SSH authentication using an image URN.
1185	    text: >
1186	        az vm create -n MyVm -g MyResourceGroup --image RedHat:RHEL:7-RAW:7.4.2018010506
1187	  - name: Create a default Windows Server VM with a private IP address.
1188	    text: >
1189	        az vm create -n MyVm -g MyResourceGroup --public-ip-address "" --image Win2012R2Datacenter
1190	  - name: Create a VM from a custom managed image.
1191	    text: >
1192	        az vm create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVm --image MyImage
1193	  - name: Create a VM from a generalized gallery image version.
1194	    text: >
1195	        az vm create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVm --image /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/myGallery/images/myImage/versions/1.0.0
1196	  - name: Create a VM from a specialized gallery image version.
1197	    text: >
1198	        az vm create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVm --image /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/myGallery/images/myImage/versions/1.0.0 --specialized
1199	  - name: Create a VM from the latest version of a gallery image
1200	    text: >
1201	        az vm create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVm --image /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/myGallery/images/myImage
1202	  - name: Create a VM by attaching to a managed operating system disk.
1203	    text: >
1204	        az vm create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVm --attach-os-disk MyOsDisk --os-type linux
1205	  - name: Create a VM by attaching to an unmanaged operating system disk from a VHD blob uri.
1206	    text: >
1207	        az vm create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVm --attach-os-disk https://vhd1234.blob.core.windows.net/vhds/osdisk1234.vhd --os-type linux --use-unmanaged-disk
1208	  - name: 'Create an Debian11 VM using a cloud-init script for configuration. See: https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/virtual-machines/linux/using-cloud-init.'
1209	    text: >
1210	        az vm create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVm --image Debian11 --custom-data MyCloudInitScript.yml
1211	  - name: Create a Debian11 VM with SSH key authentication and a public DNS entry, located on an existing virtual network and availability set.
1212	    text: |
1213	        az vm create -n MyVm -g MyResourceGroup --image Debian11 --vnet-name MyVnet --subnet subnet1 \\
1214	            --availability-set MyAvailabilitySet --public-ip-address-dns-name MyUniqueDnsName \\
1215	            --ssh-key-values @key-file
1216	  - name: Create a simple Ubuntu Linux VM with a public IP address, DNS entry, two data disks (10GB and 20GB), and then generate RSA ssh key pairs.
1217	    text: |
1218	        az vm create -n MyVm -g MyResourceGroup --public-ip-address-dns-name MyUniqueDnsName \\
1219	            --image Ubuntu2204 --data-disk-sizes-gb 10 20 --size Standard_DS2_v2 \\
1220	            --generate-ssh-keys
1221	  - name: Create a Debian11 VM using Key Vault secrets.
1222	    text: >
1223	        az keyvault certificate create --vault-name vaultname -n cert1 \\
1224	          -p "$(az keyvault certificate get-default-policy)"
1225	
1226	        secrets=$(az keyvault secret list-versions --vault-name vaultname \\
1227	          -n cert1 --query "[?attributes.enabled].id" -o tsv)
1228	
1229	        vm_secrets=$(az vm secret format -s "$secrets")
1230	
1231	
1232	        az vm create -g group-name -n vm-name --admin-username deploy  \\
1233	          --image debian11 --secrets "$vm_secrets"
1234	  - name: Create a CentOS VM with a system assigned identity. The VM will have a 'Contributor' role with access to a storage account.
1235	    text: >
1236	        az vm create -n MyVm -g rg1 --image CentOS85Gen2 --assign-identity [system] --scope /subscriptions/99999999-1bf0-4dda-aec3-cb9272f09590/MyResourceGroup/myRG/providers/Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts/storage1 --role Contributor
1237	  - name: Create a Debian11 VM with a user assigned identity.
1238	    text: >
1239	        az vm create -n MyVm -g rg1 --image Debian11 --assign-identity /subscriptions/99999999-1bf0-4dda-aec3-cb9272f09590/resourcegroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.ManagedIdentity/userAssignedIdentities/myID
1240	  - name: Create a Debian11 VM with both system and user assigned identity.
1241	    text: >
1242	        az vm create -n MyVm -g rg1 --image Debian11 --assign-identity [system] /subscriptions/99999999-1bf0-4dda-aec3-cb9272f09590/resourcegroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.ManagedIdentity/userAssignedIdentities/myID
1243	  - name: Create a vm with user assigned identity and add encryption identity for Azure disk encryption
1244	    text: >
1245	        az vm create -n MyVm -g rg1 --image Debian11 --assign-identity myID --encryption-identity /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourcegroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.ManagedIdentity/userAssignedIdentities/myID
1246	  - name: Create a VM in an availability zone in the current resource group's region.
1247	    supported-profiles: latest
1248	    text: >
1249	        az vm create -n MyVm -g MyResourceGroup --image CentOS85Gen2 --zone 1
1250	  - name: Create multiple VMs. In this example, 3 VMs are created. They are MyVm0, MyVm1, MyVm2.
1251	    text: >
1252	        az vm create -n MyVm -g MyResourceGroup --image CentOS85Gen2 --count 3
1253	  - name: Create a VM from shared gallery image
1254	    text: >
1255	        az vm create -n MyVm -g MyResourceGroup --image /SharedGalleries/{gallery_unique_name}/Images/{image}/Versions/{version}
1256	  - name: Create a VM from community gallery image
1257	    text: >
1258	        az vm create -n MyVm -g MyResourceGroup --image /CommunityGalleries/{gallery_unique_name}/Images/{image}/Versions/{version}
1259	"""

1358	helps['vm disk'] = """
1359	type: group
1360	short-summary: Manage the managed data disks attached to a VM.
1361	long-summary: >4
1362	
1363	    Azure Virtual Machines use disks as a place to store an operating system, applications, and data.
1364	    All Azure virtual machines have at least two disks: An operating system disk, and a temporary disk.
1365	    The operating system disk is created from an image, and both the operating system disk and the image are actually virtual hard disks (VHDs)
1366	    stored in an Azure storage account. Virtual machines also can have one or more data disks, that are also stored as VHDs.
1367	
1368	
1369	    Azure Managed and Unmanaged Data Disks have a maximum size of 4095 GB (with the exception of larger disks in preview). Azure Unmanaged Disks also have a maximum capacity of 4095 GB.
1370	
1371	
1372	    For more information, see:
1373	
1374	    - Azure Disks - https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/virtual-machines/managed-disks-overview.
1375	
1376	    - Larger Managed Disks in Public Preview - https://azure.microsoft.com/blog/introducing-the-public-preview-of-larger-managed-disks-sizes/
1377	
1378	    - Ultra SSD Managed Disks in Public Preview - https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/virtual-machines/disks-types

2366	    short-summary: >
2367	        The name of the operating system image as a URN alias, URN, custom image name or ID, or VHD blob URI. In addition, it also supports shared gallery image.
2368	        Please use the image alias including the version of the distribution you want to use. For example: please use Debian11 instead of Debian.'
2369	        This parameter is required unless using `--attach-os-disk.` Valid URN format: "Publisher:Offer:Sku:Version". For more information, see https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/virtual-machines/linux/cli-ps-findimage
2370	    populator-commands:
2371	      - az vm image list
2372	      - az vm image show
2373	      - az sig image-version show-shared
2374	  - name: --ssh-key-values
2375	    short-summary: Space-separated list of SSH public keys or public key file paths.
2376	examples:
2377	  - name: Create a Windows VM scale set with 5 instances, a load balancer, a public IP address, a 2GB data disk and 40GB OS disk.
2378	    text: >
2379	        az vmss create -n MyVmss -g MyResourceGroup --instance-count 5 --image Win2016Datacenter --data-disk-sizes-gb 2 --os-disk-size-gb 40
2380	  - name: Create a Linux VM scale set with an auto-generated ssh key pair, a public IP address, a DNS entry, an existing load balancer, and an existing virtual network.
2381	    text: |
2382	        az vmss create -n MyVmss -g MyResourceGroup --public-ip-address-dns-name my-globally-dns-name \\
2383	            --load-balancer MyLoadBalancer --vnet-name MyVnet --subnet MySubnet --image Ubuntu2204 \\
2384	            --generate-ssh-keys
2385	  - name: Create a Linux VM scale set from a custom image using the default existing public SSH key.
2386	    text: >
2387	        az vmss create -n MyVmss -g MyResourceGroup --image MyImage
2388	  - name: Create a Linux VM scale set with a load balancer and custom DNS servers. Each VM has a public-ip address and a custom domain name.
2389	    text: >
2390	        az vmss create -n MyVmss -g MyResourceGroup --image CentOS85Gen2 \\
2391	            --public-ip-per-vm --vm-domain-name myvmss --dns-servers 10.0.0.6 10.0.0.5
2392	  - name: 'Create a Linux VM scale set using a cloud-init script for configuration. See: https://learn.microsoft.com/azure/virtual-machines/linux/using-cloud-init'
2393	    text: >
2394	        az vmss create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVmss --image Debian11 --custom-data MyCloudInitScript.yml
2395	  - name: Create a VMSS from a generalized gallery image version.
2396	    text: >
2397	        az vmss create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVmss --image /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/myGallery/images/myImage/versions/1.0.0
2398	  - name: Create a VMSS from a specialized gallery image version.
2399	    text: >
2400	        az vmss create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVmss --image /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/myGallery/images/myImage/versions/1.0.0 --specialized
2401	  - name: Create a VMSS from the latest version of a gallery image
2402	    text: >
2403	        az vmss create -g MyResourceGroup -n MyVmss --image /subscriptions/00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000/resourceGroups/myRG/providers/Microsoft.Compute/galleries/myGallery/images/myImage
2404	  - name: Create a Debian11 VM scaleset using Key Vault secrets.
2405	    text: >

2407	          -p "$(az keyvault certificate get-default-policy)"
2408

2410	          -n cert1 --query "[?attributes.enabled].id" -o tsv)
2411

2413	
2414

2416	          --image Debian11 --secrets "$vm_secrets"

2420	  - name: Create a Debian11 VM scaleset with a user assigned identity.

2423	  - name: Create a vmss with user assigned identity and add encryption identity for Azure disk encryption
